[183] UiParts should not store a reference to the primaryStage* UiPart: move setIcon() into MainWindowrnrnUiPart::setIcon() is only used by MainWindow. Furthermore, UiPartsrnshould not be allowed to change the primary stage's icon at their whimrnand fancy, as it may lead to multiple UiParts conflicting with eachrnother because they all want to set the primary stage's icons.rnrnSo, make it clear that only MainWindow is allowed to do this by movingrnUiPart::setIcon() into MainWindow, and making it private.rnrn* UiPart: move setIcon() into FxViewUtilrnrnUiPart::setIcon() does not depend on any internal data of UiPart, andrnthus is better suited to be in an external utility class as a staticrnmethod. This is done to make it clear that calling setIcon() will notrnmodify the state of any objects, besides the Stage passed in as anrnargument.rnrn* FxViewUtil: rename setIcon() to setStageIcon()rnrnThis is done to make it clear that the method operates on a Stage.rnrn* UiPart: push down primaryStagernrnCurrently, all UiParts store a reference to their primaryStage, whichrnmeans that they can modify the primaryStage at their own whim and fancy.rnrnWe want to prevent that -- UiParts should not be able to access thernprimaryStage as it makes it hard to reason about which UiPart isrncontrolling the primaryStage and which is not. As such, we want tornremove the reference to the primaryStage from all UiParts.rnrnOf all the UiParts, we note that only MainWindow requires a reference tornthe primaryStage. All other UiParts do not, and SHOULD NOT, keep arnreference to the primaryStage.rnrnSo, we push down the `primaryStage` field from UiPart to MainWindowrnonly. All other UiParts thus effectively lose access to thernprimaryStage, which is a good thing for encapsulation.rnrn* UiPartLoader: rename loadUiPart() to initUiPart()rnrnAll other variants of loadUiPart() will reconstruct the UiPart based onrnthe value of fx:controller in its FXML file.rnrnOnly loadUiPart(T seedUiPart) does not -- it simply sets up the FXMLrnscene graph using the existing UiPart object provided.rnrnTo highlight the difference in behaviour of this method from the others,rnrename this method to `initUiPart()`.rnrn* UiPartLoader: add single argument variant of loadUiPart()rn

build.gradle: add `run` and `runShadow` tasks (#178)The `run` and `runShadow` tasks provide a convenient way for developersrnto run the built application from its *.class files or the built fat JARrnrespectively.rnrnThis is accomplished using the application plugin[1] which implementsrnthe 'run' task.rnrnThe shadow plugin, which we already use, will automatically detect thern`application` plugin and will integrate with it[2], providing thern`runShadow` task. It also knows that `mainClassName` should be usedrnas the Main-Class of the JAR manifest, so we don't need to specifyrnthat anymore.rnrnWe add the `mainClassName` and `plugin` lines OUTSIDE of thern`allprojects` block because the question of which class should be runrnis Gradle project-specific and only applicable to the root project.rnrn[1] https://docs.gradle.org/current/userguide/application_plugin.htmlrn[2] http://imperceptiblethoughts.com/shadow/#integrating_with_application_plugin

checkstyle: check for trailing whitespace  #179 (#180)* codestyle: remove trailing whitespacernrnSome lines in the code look like an empty line, but actually containrnspaces.rnrnTo be consistent with the rest of the code, let's make sure all emptyrnlines are actually empty.rnrn* checkstyle: check for trailing whitespacernrnTo ensure that no more trailing whitespace is introduced into our codernbase, add a check for it.rn

[188] Construct StatusBarFooter in FXML fullyStatusBarFooter currently constructs and sets up its StatusBar controlsrnusing pure code.rnrnThe StatusBar control is actually a real control that can be initializedrndirectly in the FXML file. We can avoid placeholder elements and makernthings simpler by just doing that.rnrnNow, one may think: This means Scene Builder cannot edit this FXML filernany more!, since the StatusBar control comes from controlsfx, which isrnnot supported by Scene Builder by default. However,rnrn1. Scene Builder can actually be configured[1] to support the customrn   controls from controlsfx, allowing it to edit the FXML file.rnrn2. Having too many placeholder nodes, and constructing the actual scenern   graph in code, kind of defeats the advantage of FXML which is torn   construct the scene graph declaratively without code.rnrn[1] http://stackoverflow.com/a/30078204

checkstyle: accept LF, CR or CRLF as line endings (#194)Checking out this repo on a Windows machine with a vanilla Git config,rnthen running `gradlew.bat checkstyleMain` gives the following errors:rnrn[ant:checkstyle] [ERROR] C:Userspyokaganpykaddressbook-level4srcmainjavarnseeduaddressMainApp.java:0: File does not end with a newline. [NewlineAtEndOfFrnile]rn[ant:checkstyle] [ERROR] C:Userspyokaganpykaddressbook-level4srcmainjavarnseeduaddresscommonscoreComponentManager.java:0: File does not end with a newrnline. [NewlineAtEndOfFile]rn[ant:checkstyle] [ERROR] C:Userspyokaganpykaddressbook-level4srcmainjavarnseeduaddresscommonscoreConfig.java:0: File does not end with a newline. [NewrnlineAtEndOfFile]rn[ant:checkstyle] [ERROR] C:Userspyokaganpykaddressbook-level4srcmainjavarnseeduaddresscommonscoreEventsCenter.java:0: File does not end with a newlinern. [NewlineAtEndOfFile]rn[ant:checkstyle] [ERROR] C:Userspyokaganpykaddressbook-level4srcmainjavarnseeduaddresscommonscoreGuiSettings.java:0: File does not end with a newline.rn [NewlineAtEndOfFile]rn[ant:checkstyle] [ERROR] C:Userspyokaganpykaddressbook-level4srcmainjavarnseeduaddresscommonscoreLogsCenter.java:0: File does not end with a newline.rn[NewlineAtEndOfFile]rn[ant:checkstyle] [ERROR] C:Userspyokaganpykaddressbook-level4srcmainjavarnseeduaddresscommonscoreMessages.java:0: File does not end with a newline. [NrnewlineAtEndOfFile]rn[ant:checkstyle] [ERROR] C:Userspyokaganpykaddressbook-level4srcmainjavarnseeduaddresscommonscoreUnmodifiableObservableList.java:0: File does not endrnwith a newline. [NewlineAtEndOfFile]rn...etcrnrnThis goes on for every single Java file.rnrnThis is because this repo's files uses LF as the line separator.rnHowever, the default lineSeparator value of the NewlineAtEndOfFilerncheck is CRLF on Windows[1], hence these errors.rnrnOne may argue that we could switch on `core.autocrlf` in Git, whichrnwould tell Git to automatically convert all LF line endings to CRLF,rnthus avoiding this problem. However, this not only places an additionalrnburden on Windows users to configure Git properly, it also does notrnhandle the use cases where a developer is not using Git. The developerrnmay, for example, instead get hold of the repo by downloading the ZIPrnfile using Github's Download as ZIP[2] functionality, and will thusrnstill have this problem as the downloaded ZIP contents will stillrncontain LF line endings.rnrnThus, we should either switch the lineSeparator property to lf,rnaccepting only LF line endings, or lf_cr_crlf, accepting LF, CR orrnCRLF line endings. (Checkstyle does not support just LF and CRLF only)rnrnHowever, some developers may have `core.autocrlf` accidentally set, orrnmay even prefer to use CRLF line endings in their working copy. As such,rnlet's go the route of allowing LF, CR or CRLF as line endings.rnrn[1] http://checkstyle.sourceforge.net/config_misc.html#NewlineAtEndOfFilern[2] https://github.com/se-edu/addressbook-level4/archive/master.zip

checkstyle: ensure curly brackets have whitespace around them #181 (#182)* codestyle: ensure curly brackets are separated by whitespacernrnThe Java coding standard[1] requires that curly brackets ({}) bernsurrounded by whitespace.rnrnHowever, there are several violations of this requirement in the codernbase. e.g.rnrnprotected void raise(BaseEvent event){rn-------------------------------------^rnSpace required before '{'rnrnFix all of these code style violations.rnrn[1] https://oss-generic.github.io/process/codingstandards/coding-standards-java.html#methodsrnrn* checkstyle: ensure curly brackets have whitespace around themrnrnThere used to be methods in the code base where the curly brackets ({})rnare not separated by whitespace:rnrnprotected void raise(BaseEvent event){rn-------------------------------------^rnSpace required before '{'rnrnOur checkstyle configuration failed to catch these errors because we didrnnot tell checkstyle to check for the LCURLY, RCURLY and SLIST (statementrnlist) tokens. Fix this in the checkstyle config file so that such codernstyle violations will not happen again.rn

[#186] Construct BrowserPanel in FXML (#208)* Construct BrowserPanel using FXMLrnrnThe DeveloperGuide states that the layout of individual UiParts arernspecified in matching `.fxml` files. e.g. The layout ofrn`MainWindow.java` is specified in `MainWindow.fxml`.rnrnWhile this is true for almost all UiParts, there is one oddball UiPartrnthat does not have a corresponding `.fxml` file -- BrowserPanel.rnrnFor consistency with the rest of the UiParts, let's construct thernBrowserPanel using FXML rather than using code.rnrn* Remove DefaultBrowserPlaceHolderScreen.fxmlrnrnIt is not being used at all.rn

Adding AppVeyor support to this project willrnallow us to easily ensure that our tests do not break on Windows.rnrnAdd an appveyor.yml file that will teach AppVeyor how to build thisrnproject and run its tests.rnrnUpdate our documentation to explain to developers how to set up AppVeyorrnon their own repositories.rnrnFor now, we will run our tests with 64-bit Java only, since the projectrndoes not use any native libraries and thus is unlikely to have anyrnarchitecture-specific bugs. In the future, should we use any nativernlibraries, the appveyor.yml file should be updated to run our tests onrnboth 32-bit and 64-bit Java.rnrn[1] https://www.appveyor.com/

[#221] Rework how TypicalTestPersons exposes its persons (#224)* TypicalTestPersons: remove repetition of typical persons listrnrnThe list of typical persons is repeated inrnloadAddressBookWithSampleData() and getTypicalPersons(). DRY up the codernby making getTypicalPersons() the authoritative source.rnrn* TypicalTestPersons: make TestPerson fields non-staticrnrnThroughout the code base, TypicalTestPersons is typically used in thernfollowing fashion so that tests can access the test persons using arnshorter variable name, e.g.:rnrnTypicalTestPersons td = new TypicalTestPersons();rntd.alice, td.benson etc.rnrnHowever, with such code, Eclipse will give the following warning:rnrnThe static field TypicalTestPersons.alice should be accessed in arnstatic way.rnrnThis is because these TestPerson fields are static. This is problematicrnbecause these fields can be accessed without first constructing arnTypicalTestPersons object (e.g. with `TypicalTestPersons.alice`,rn`TypicalTestPersons.benson` etc.), which could potentially lead tornNullPointerExceptions (if a TypicalTestPersons object was notrnconstructed yet) or state leaks (if a test modifies the TestPersons)rnwhich are hard to debug.rnrnAs such, let's make these TestPerson fields non-static.rn

[#190] Make ReadOnlyAddressBook truly read-only (#199)* Remove redundant get empty address book methodsrnrnIt seems strange that we have AddressBook#getEmptyAddressBook() andrnTestUtil#generateEmptyAddressBook() methods, when a simplern`new AddressBook()` will give us what we want.rnrn* Fully encapsulate UniquePersonList and UniqueTagList within AddressBookrnrnReadOnlyAddressBook declares the following methods:rnrn* `UniqueTagList getUniqueTagList();`rnrn* `List<Tag> getTagList();`rnrn* `UniquePersonList getUniquePersonList();`rnrn* `List<ReadOnlyPerson> getPersonList();`rnrnAs we can see, there is some redundancy; both `getUniqueTagList()` andrn`getTagList()` conceptually do the same thing, and bothrn`getUniquePersonList()` and `getPersonList()` conceptually dornthe same thing as well.rnrnSo, to simplify the API we need to pick one set of APIs: either the onesrnthat return `UniqueXList`, or the ones that return `List<X>`.rnrnGoing with the API that returns `List<X>` is more beneficial thanrn`UniqueXList`: Lists are widely used throughout our code and thernstandard library, and thus returning a list would be much morernconvenient for developers. `UniquePersonList` and `UniqueTagList`, onrnthe other hand, only implement the `Iterable` interface, and are thusrnslightly more annoying to write code with.rnrnHowever, there is a deeper problem as well: `UniquePersonList` andrn`UniqueTagList` both contain mutating methods, which violates therncontract of `ReadOnlyAddressBook` to provide a read-only view to thernaddress book. We could solve this by introducingrn`ReadOnlyUniquePersonList` and `ReadOnlyUniqueTagList` interfaces, butrnas argued above, by virtue of not implementing the `List`rninterface these objects are more annoying to deal with and thus it isrnlikely better to not return them at all.rnrnAs such, this commit removes the `getUniqueTagList()` andrn`getUniquePersonList()` methods. In addition, we also remove all of thernmethods of `AddressBook` that take a `UniquePersonList` orrn`UniqueTagList`, thus fully encapsulating these classes withinrn`AddressBook`. This not only solves the contract violation problem asrndiscussed above, it also reduces coupling as users will no longer needrnto depend directly on `UniquePersonList` and `UniqueTagList` any more.rnrn* ModelManager: merge two similar constructorsrnrnBoth ModelManager(AddressBook, UserPrefs) andrnModelManager(ReadOnlyAddressBook, UserPrefs) both do exactly the samernthing. Let's DRY up the code by merging them into one singlernconstructor.rnrnThe author notes that the `userPrefs` argument is currently not evenrnused. However, fixing this is outside the scope of this commit.rnrn* AddressBook: replace getPersons() with getPersonList()rnrnReadOnlyAddressBook has a getPersonList() method which returns its listrnof persons as a List<ReadOnlyPerson>rnrnAddressBook has a getPersons() method which returns its list of personsrnas an ObservableList<Person>.rnrnSimplify the API by merging these methods together, by makingrngetPersonList() return an ObservableList<ReadOnlyPerson> and removingrngetPersons().rnrn* ReadOnlyAddressBook: make getTagList() return an ObservableListrnrnEven though there are currently no callers that require the return valuernto be an ObservableList, this is still done for consistency withrngetPersonList() and to make it easier to implement future UI featuresrnsuch as a listing of all tags.rnrn* fixup! Fully encapsulate UniquePersonList and UniqueTagList within AddressBookrnrn* fixup! Fully encapsulate UniquePersonList and UniqueTagList within AddressBookrn

Implement Travis CI line ending checksIn our repository, we want:nn* All text files to use only LF ('n') as their line endings. Not CRLFn  ('rn')nn* All text files to end with a newline (Newline at EOF).nnSo, ideally, we should have checks that automatically check for thesenrequirements in our repository.nnHowever, we can't impose these checks on all developers, namely Windowsndevelopers. They could be using either LF or CRLF (e.g. if the developernactivated Git's core.autocrlf configuration). Even if we did, we can'tnguarantee that developers do not bypass these checks. As such, we havento implement these checks on the Travis CI level instead.nnThe next question is how do we implement these checks. Checkstyle isnalready helping us with that, but it is not completely effective as itndoes not check *all* text files -- it only checks the source files whichnare used for compilation.  This means that it does not check things likenresource files (CSS and FXML files), test data and documentation.nnWhile we could probably teach it to check all files, we meet anothernproblem; Checkstyle does not know what a text file is. At best, we cannonly give it a filter of file extensions to check.nnOn the other hand, Git knows the difference between text files andnbinary files. As such, let's implement some shell scripts that will usenGit's facilities to implement our line ending checks on all text files.nThese checks will be run on Travis CI, thus guaranteeing that masternwill not have any more line ending problems.nnThese checks are implemented in POSIX shell scripts so that Travis CInwould not need to download any additional dependencies in order to runnthem. Furthermore, developers running Linux or Macs can also run themnlocally without downloading additional dependencies as well. Windowsndevs would be unable to run them, but then again these line endingnchecks are not useful to them because as mentioned above, Windows devsnmay be using CRLF line endings anyway.n

Implement Travis CI trailing whitespace checkWhile our checkstyle configuration already checks for trailingnwhitespace in our java files, it does not cover all text files in ournrepository. Notably: our documentation files and other configurationnfiles such as `build.gradle`.nnWhile we could probably coax checkstyle and gradle to check for thesenfiles, it is much easier to just hook onto our existing Travis CInchecks architecture to implement this check.nnTrailing whitespace should be considered an error, however we treatntrailing whitespace in markdown (`*.md`) files as warnings instead tonaccomodate developers who prefer to edit documentation using the GitHubnweb interface which does not provide facilities to easily detect andnremove trailing whitespace.n

UiPart: implement FXML loading constructorThere's quite a lot of boilerplate involved if a developer wishes tonimplement a new UiPart. The developer needs to override:nn* `setNode()`nn* `getFxmlPath()`nn* potentially `setPlaceholder()`nnand think of what the sane thing is to do for each of these methods. Innaddition, to make the API pleasant to use, developers need to implementna static `load()` method. In that method, the developer needs to furtherndecide which of the three overloaded `UiPartLoader::loadUiPart()`nmethods to call.nnThe reason why so much boilerplate is required is because the currentnimplementation, through `UiPartLoader`, places the responsibility ofncreating new `UiPart` instances (the controller) on the JavaFXnFXMLLoader. However, FXMLLoader can only use the no-arg constructor ofnUiParts. As such, we need extra code to workaround this limitation innorder to pass arguments into UiParts, leading to the above boilerplatencode.nnTo fix this problem, let's do two things:nnFirstly, we introduce a stricter definition of a UiPart: it contains anscene graph with a root node of a certain type T. This node can benretrieved with the new `getRoot()` getter.nnSecondly, we introduce new `UiPart(URL)` and `UiPart(String)`nconstructors. These UiPart constructors will construct the UiPartninstance *first* before passing it to the FXMLLoader. In other words, wenare now directly in control of our own constructors, which removes thenneed for the above boilerplate methods. A simple UiPart subclass wouldnlook like:nnpublic class NewUiPart extends UiPart<Pane> {nprivate final Object arg;nn@FXMLnprivate TextBox myNode;nnpublic NewUiPart(Object arg) {nsuper(NewUiPart.fxml);nn// We can now initialize final fields!nthis.arg = arg;nn// We can also access nodes in our FXML scene graphn// immediately!nmyNode.setText(hello world!);n}n}nnNotice how short the code is, as well as how it does not need tonimplement a static `load()` method or depend on UiPartLoader.nnOne problem is that FXMLLoader does not allow passing in a controllerninstance if the FXML file has a fx:controller attribute. Without thisnattribute, JavaFX FXML editors could potentially not be able to link thencontroller class with the FXML file[1], as they do not know what thencontroller class is. However, given the amount of code we save bynadopting this architecture, this seems to be a worthwhile trade-off.nnThere's lot of ui parts which currently depend on the old way of doingnthings, though. For now, let's mark the no-arg UiPart constructor, asnwell as the setNode(), getFxmlPath() and setPlaceholder() methods asndeprecated. Convert setNode() and getFxmlPath() into non-abstractnmethods so that UiParts who have migrated over to the new API do notnneed to implement them.  Also, mark the UiPartLoader methods asndeprecated since UiParts using the new API should not need to call them.nnIn future commits, we will port each UiPart incrementally to use the newn`UiPart(String)` constructor. When all code has been finally ported, wencan then remove the deprecated code.nnWhile we are also here, let's add some tests for UiPart.nn[1] It should be noted, however, that Gluon Scene Builder (the usualnFXML editor used by developers) does not actually link the FXML filenwith its controller class, so this commit may actually be a strictnimprovement with little drawbacks.n

Make Travis CI output less verboseGradle utilises different levels for logging (seenhttps://docs.gradle.org/current/userguide/logging.html).nn.travis.yml is set to execute gradle with '-i'. This means that lognmessages with 'INFO' level and above are printed to stdout, which is anmore verbose level than the default.nnThe reasons for using 'INFO' level are as follows:nn  1. To ensure that the tests are actually running (instead of an emptyn Gradle task in its place).nn  2. To determine which test stalled the CI (occasionally occurs due ton either Travis issues or faulty tests).nnHowever, such detailed logging also generates a large quantity ofnlogging information from non-test-runners, which pollutes the log andnmakes it extremely verbose without providing any additional usefulndiagnosis information for tests.nnAs such, remove '-i' to disable 'INFO' logging level, and also modifynbuild.gradle to ensure that the progress of the test runner is stillnbeing reported.n

Add UnusedImports check in checkstyleUnused imports are a code smell as they make it less clear which classes anJava file depends on. Our checkstyle configuration does not presently checknfor unused imports, so let's add an UsedImports check which does just that.nnThere is already a slightly similarly-named check in our checkstyle.xml filencalled RedundantImport. Its name could mislead readers into thinking that itnactually checks for unused imports as well, as an unused import could benconsidered to be redundant. However, it doesn't actually do that. Becausenan import is redundant ifn1. It is a duplicate of another import.n2. The class non-statically imported is from the java.lang package.n3. The class non-statically imported is from the same package as then   current package.n

Make Eclipse Checkstyle Plugin recognizes all existing modulesSeveral existing enabled modules in our Checkstyle configuration file,nsuch as TypeNameCheck and ConstantNameCheck, are being silentlynignored by the Eclipse Checkstyle Plugin.nnThis is because given a module FooCheck, Checkstyle recognizes bothnits short name (Foo) and its fully qualified name (FooCheck) asnnames of that module. However, the Eclipse Checkstyle Plugin only usesnshort name convention, and thus does not recognize modules that arenbeing referred to by their full names.nnFix this by modifying our Checkstyle configuration file to use the shortnnames of these modules, so that both Checkstyle and the EclipsenCheckstyle Plugin will recognize them.n

Add Asciidoctor Gradle pluginGitHub Flavored Markdown does not support the specialized features thatnthis project requires, such as use of colors and easy conversion tonother file formats. AsciiDoc, like Markdown, uses a readable syntaxnthat is easy to learn. It is also supported by GitHub preview. Innaddition, AsciiDoc supports more features, such as auto-numbering ofnsections, auto-generation of table of contents and admonition blocks.nStyling is also possible using custom CSS stylesheets. Furthermore,nAsciiDoc is designed to make it easy to translate documents to othernformats, and Asciidoctor makes it simple for users to generate HTMLnfiles from asciidoc documents.nnConverting to PDF:nnWhile Asciidoctor supports conversion to PDF, Asciidoctor PDF isncurrently an alpha release and does not support useful features such asnfont colors. Styling must also be done separately in an Asciidoctor PDFntheme file, which is different from the CSS used for HTML files.nnTo convert documentation to PDF format, we suggest using the browser'sn'save as PDF' function on the generated HTML files instead.nnStylesheets:nnasciidoctor.css is the default stylesheet by Asciidoctor andngh-pages.css is the customized version used by the documentation.nHaving our customizations in a separate file instead of editing thendefault stylesheet makes it easy for developers to swap in othernstylesheets which import the default stylesheet, such as those availablenat https://github.com/darshandsoni/asciidoctor-skins.nncopyStylesheets Gradle task:nnAsciidoctor suggests using the resources method to copy additionalnresources (in this case, CSS stylesheets) to the build directory.nHowever, this does not work as Asciidoctor tries to generate thenHTML files before copying the resources, as discussed innhttps://github.com/asciidoctor/asciidoctor-gradle-plugin/issues/178.nnLet's create a copyStylesheets task to copy the necessary resourcesnbefore running Asciidoctor instead, a workaround suggested innthe issue mentioned above.nnAsciidoctor attributes:nnEven though all AsciiDoc files use the same images directory,nimagesDir attribute must be set in each individual file instead ofnin Asciidoctor's attributes. Otherwise, GitHub preview wronglynlinks to image.png instead of images/image.png so images are notndisplayed in the preview.n

[#342] Travis CI: cache dependencies (#347)Gradle dependencies are not cached in Travis builds.rnrnConsequently, the dependencies are re-downloaded in every build.rnrnLet's teach Travis to cache Gradle dependencies using the recommendedrnconfigurations from Travis CI documentation [1].rnrnIn our experiments, when cache is not enabled, it takes 26.68 secondsrnto run Gradle assemble task, which includes downloading Gradle and therndependencies. When cache is enabled, Travis will tar up all the cachedrndirectories and upload them to S3. So the cache is not network-local,rnand the download time will be bound to network bandwidth and DNSrnresolutions for S3. In the experiment, it takes 5.83 seconds to pullrndown the cache from S3 and another 10.75 seconds to finish the assemblerntask. At the end of the build, Travis will also check whether the cachernis updated. If it is, Travis will create a new archive and upload it tornS3. This check adds another 1.48 seconds overhead even when the cachernis not updated. So a rough estimate is that the build time will bernreduced by around 10 seconds when cache is enabled. Reasons for thernshorter build time now may be because Travis downloads the dependenciesrnfrom S3 in bulk instead of making multiple requests (one for eachrndependency).rnrnFor more details on how caching works in Travis, please refer to [2].rnrn[1] https://docs.travis-ci.com/user/languages/java/#Cachingrn[2] https://docs.travis-ci.com/user/caching/#How-does-caching-work

[#319] Checkstyle: add CommentsIndentation rule (#361)Our coding standard for Java requires a comment to be indented to rnmatch the indentation of the code it describes. This rule is notrnenforced by checkstyle.rnrnLet's enforce this rule by adding the checkstyle rule CommentsIndentation.

[#319] Checkstyle: fix MethodName supplied expression (#366)Test case method names are expected to follow the formatrnfeatureBeingTested_scenario_expectedResult.rnrnHowever, following aspects of the above naming conventionrnare not enforced by checkstyle:rn1. only one consecutive underscore between two partsrn2. no more than 2 underscoresrn3. each part should of the name should start with a lower case letterrn4. do not end with a symbolrnrnLet's update the relevant regex in the checkstyle config filernto enforce the 4 aspects mentioned above.

[#319] Checkstyle: disallow single line conditional statements (#362)Checkstyle allows single line conditionals like this:rnrnif(something) foo();rnrnSuch statements can potentially introduce bugs like the codernbelow where it appears like bar() is attached to the condition rnbut is not:rnrnif(something) foo();rnbar();rnrnIt can also cause some code coverage checkers to producerninaccurate coverage statistics as it goes by the lines covered.rnrnLet's disallow single line conditionals by removing the allowSingleLineStatement rnproperty, which defaults to false.

[#371] Remove uses of real domain names (#375)Potentially genuine email addresses are used in our documentation andrntesting code, e.g. bobby@gmail.com, hans@google.com, alice@yahoo.com.rnrnWe don't want to help spam bots send spam to them.rnrnLet's change these potentially genuine email address to @example.com.

[#319] Checkstyle: prevent upper case abbreviations in names (#360)Upper case abbreviations in names (e.g. HTML in exportHTMLSource)rnare not allowed by our coding standard (it should be exportHtmlSource rninstead) but that rule is not enforced by checkstyle .rnrnLet's teach checkstyle to reject upper case abbreviations in names rnby adding AbbreviationAsWordInName rule which rejectsrnconsecutive upper case letters in identifier names.rnrnIn cases where there are consecutive capital letters due to wordrnboundaries around single-lettered words, such as inrnu00e2u0080u009ccanIHasReviewu00e2u0080u009d, we can make use of the allowedAbbreviations property tornwhitelist them. We are not relaxing the allowedAbbreviationLength to >1rnas single-lettered words are uncommon in identifier names, andrnwhitelisting any legitimate cases is a suitable solution.

[#319] Checkstyle: enforce @clause order (#365)Our coding standard requires @clauses in Javadoc comments rnto be in the order:rn@author, @version, @param, @return, @throws, @exception, @see,rn@since, @serial, @serialField, @serialData, @deprecatedrnThis rule is not enforced by checkstyle.rnrnKeeping the order of at-clauses organized results in the javadocsrnbeing more readable in code form. This is important as this type ofrndocumentation is typically read more often inside the code than it isrnas processed text.rnrnLet's fix this by adding AtclauseOrder rule. It checks that the orderrnof @clauses follows the tagOrder property value order.

[#319] Checkstyle: require default branch in switch statements (#378)Our coding standard requires each switch statement to include a rndefault branch, even if it contains no code. [#293] Implement a IndexUtil#oneToZeroIndex() abstraction (#331)i - 1 is sometimes used to convert 'i' from a one-based index to arnzero-based index.rnrnComments have to be added to describe the purpose of i - 1, as it isrnnot obvious whether we are taking the item before 'i', or whether we arernconverting 'i' from a one-based index into a zero-based index, whichrndecreases code readability.rnrnLet's implement a IndexUtil#oneToZeroIndex(int) method which returns thernzero-based index given the one-based index as input.rnrnThe use of IndexUtil.oneToZeroIndex(int) removes the need for a commentrnwhen we convert 'i' from a one-based index to a zero-based index.

[#270] Set up workflow for asciidocs (#302)As discussed in fae87009249fc5a0084ea0d4fd28d1d8bf312921, we arernmigrating the documentation from GitHub Flavored Markdown to AsciiDoc.rnrnLet's teach Travis to generate HTML files with Asciidoctor using thernAsciiDoc files inside the 'docs' directory. Generated files are thenrnpushed to gh-pages branch for commits to the master branch.rnrnFor the deploy script to work, maintainers will then have to:rn 1. Create a GitHub machine account and grant it access to this reporn 2. Generate an access token and put it as an encrypted environmentrn variable in Travis settings.rnrnWe use personal access tokens instead of SSH deploy keys to grantrnTravis push access to the repo as they can be set up easily via GitHub'srnand Travis' websites, unlike SSH keys which require additional tools.rnrnHowever, personal access tokens grant access to all of a user's repos.rnIf a user's access token is used, others with write access to the repornmay change the deploy script to print the token and hence gain access tornthe user's repos. Thus, we create a separate GitHub user accountrn(machine account) to handle deployment. This way, only the repo is putrnat risk in the case of a leak.rnrnAsciidoctor suggests using the Gradle Git Plugin to publish files torngh-pages[1]. However, setting up is more complicated and lessrncustomization is allowed.rnrnTravis also supports GitHub Pages Deployment[2]. However, it does notrnmaintain history for generated files, storing only the most recentrnversion, and the commit message cannot be customised to show whichrncommit the files are generated from. This can be problematic ifrndeployment fails as it is harder to identify which version ofrndocumentation is being deployed.rnrnIn deploy_github_pages.sh, we use git credentials to store the personalrnaccess token instead of adding the token to the repo url. GitHub printsrnthe repo url when there is an error for certain commands, so usingrncredentials ensures that the token is not printed to Travis logs.rnrn[1] http://asciidoctor.github.io/asciidoctor-gradle-examples/#_publish_to_github_pages_examplern[2] https://docs.travis-ci.com/user/deployment/pages/

GuiRobot: Add pauseForHuman(int)The current uses of `guiRobot.sleep()` in our gui tests can bencategorized into two groups:nn  (A) To prevent the tests from executing too fast, as that prevents usn  from visually examining the progression of the test.nn  (B) To wait for something to happen on the JavaFX Application thread.nnBoth types of uses of `guiRobot.sleep()` are undesirable. Group (A)nunfairly makes our GUI tests slower in headless mode, as in headlessnmode we can't visually examine GUI test progression anyway. Group (B)nis wrong and can lead to flaky tests, as sleeping for a set amount ofntime does not guarantee that what we are waiting for actually occurs onnthe JavaFX Application thread.nnLet's start by cleaning up group (A), by adding GuiRobot#pauseForHuman(int)nto make the usage of pausing the test execution clearer, and also tonallow headless mode to disable these unnecessary pauses.nnWe then replace all usages of `guiRobot.sleep()` in group (A) withn`guiRobot.pauseForHuman()`.nnThe remaining usages of `guiRobot.sleep()` in the code base fall intongroup (B), which we shall clean up in the next commit.n

ErrorDialogGuiTest: Implement smart wait for showErrorDialogs()ErrorDialogGuiTest#showErrorDialogs() posts a 'DataSavingExceptionEvent'.nThis event is caught by the GUI, which launches an Alert dialog box.nnThe GUI launches the dialog box, waits for 1000ms, and assumes that thendialog box is open after 1000ms. The delay does not guarantee that thenAlert dialog box is actually opened after 1000ms has passed.nnLet's add guiRobot.waitForEvent() to add incremental wait, and also ensurenthat the Alert dialog box is actually opened before proceeding. It willnalso fail if our wait becomes too long.n

GuiRobot#pauseForHuman(int): Remove duration parameterSome events are easy to examine and require less time for pausing, whilenother events require more human processing time. Therefore, the testsnrequire different values of time to sleep.nnHowever, this makes it difficult to use GuiRobot#pauseForHuman(int) asndevelopers need to determine the desirable waiting time.nnLet's remove the duration parameter, and standardise the waiting timento be 250ms, which is sufficient for events that require more humannprocessing time.n

[#502] Revamp sleep() for Gui tests (#503)The current uses of `guiRobot.sleep()` in our gui tests can berncategorized into two groups:rnrn  (A) To prevent the tests from executing too fast, as that prevents usrn  from visually examining the progression of the test.rnrn  (B) To wait for something to happen on the JavaFX Application thread.rnrnBoth types of uses of `guiRobot.sleep()` are undesirable. Group (A)rnunfairly makes our GUI tests slower in headless mode, as in headlessrnmode we can't visually examine GUI test progression anyway. Group (B)rnis wrong and can lead to flaky tests, as sleeping for a set amount ofrntime does not guarantee that what we are waiting for actually occurs onrnthe JavaFX Application thread.rnrnLet'srn- Add GuiRobot#pauseForHuman() (for group A) for pauses that are merelyrn  for human observations. We are able to disable these pauses in rn  headless mode.rn- Add guiRobot.waitForEvent() (for group B) with incremental waits, sorn  that we are able to wait for events in JavaFX Application thread,rn  instead of waiting for a fixed interval and assuming that the eventsrn  happened.

Add ListElementPointerThe native ListIteratoru00e2u0080u0099s cursor does not point to an element.nRather, it points in between elements. As a result, alternatingncalls of ListIterator#next() and ListIterator#previous() returnnthe same element.nnThis behaviour is not suitable for implementing the functionalitynof allowing up and down buttons to return the previous and nextninput respectively.nnAs a step towards allowing up and down buttons to get previous andnnext input respectively, letu00e2u0080u0099s create ListElementPointer.nListElementPointer has an index that works as a pointer to an elementnin the list. This allows us to iterate through the list whilenproviding better code clarity.nnWe have tried to create a class that wraps around ListIterator, butnit does not work well because the cursor still does not point to annelement.nnAlso, we have tried to create a PeekingListIterator(an extensionnof PeekingIterator [1]), in which we use peekNext() and peekPrevious()nto get the next and previous elements accordingly. One of the waysnis to override the next() and previous() methods such that they donnot return anything. However, this would violate the Iteratoru00e2u0080u0099snsemantics. Another way is to not override both methods, and simplynignore the return values i.e we only access the next and previousnelements by using peekNext() and peekPrevious() respectively.nHowever, this isnu00e2u0080u0099t intuitive to future developers who may wondernwhy we are ignoring the return values.nn[1]: http://google.github.io/guava/releases/21.0/api/docs/com/google/common/collect/PeekingIterator.htmln

Allow up and down buttons to get previous and next input respectivelyThe user is only able to see their previously typed commands throughnthe history command.nnThe user may need to access their previously typed commands quickly innorder to fix a previous typo, or to reuse the input for anothernvariation.nnLet's add a function that allows users to retrieve the previous andnnext input in the history by pressing the up and down arrow keysnrespectively.n

[#557] ParserUtil: Update header comments on Optional usage (#558)ParserUtil#parseX(Optional) methods currently take in an Optional.rnrnThis violates the usage of Java Optional. check-eof-newline: handle filenames with spacescheck-eof-newline.sh doesn't properly handle filenames with spaces,ninstead treating them as multiple files instead.nnFor example, we can create a file whose name has spaces, e.g.n'filename with spaces.txt'. Ensure that the file has some content insidenso that Git will detect it as a text file so it will be checked byncheck-eof-newline.sh:nnecho 'content' >'filename with spaces.txt'nnThen use git-add to track the file:nngit add 'filename with spaces.txt'nnThen run check-eof-newline.sh:nn./config/travis/check-eof-newline.shnncheck-eof-newline.sh will then spew out the following errors:nntail: cannot open './filename' for reading: No such file or directoryntail: cannot open './with' for reading: No such file or directoryntail: cannot open './spaces.txt' for reading: No such file or directorynnWhile this won't cause check-eof-newline.sh to error out (it will simplynignore those bogus filenames), it is still incorrect behavior since thenfile 'filename with spaces.txt' doesn't actually get checked by thenscript.nnThis happens because when check-eof-newline.sh is reading the list ofnfilenames from git-grep, the IFS variable is not set, and thus the shellnwill split the lines of filenames on <space>, <tab> and <newline>,nresulting in filenames with spaces getting split into multiplenfilenames.nnFix this by explicitly setting the IFS variable to <newline> beforenreading from git-grep, so that the lines of filenames will only be splitnon newline boundaries -- filenames with spaces will be preserved.nnSee http://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/009695399/utilities/xcu_chap02.html#tag_02_05_03nfor more info on the IFS variable.n

However,nthe code does not reflect this behaviour.nnThe constructor should use create a defensive copy of the list tonprevent unintentional modifications to the backing list whenever thenlist passed in as parameter is modified.nnLetu00e2u0080u0099s update ListElementPointer(List<String>) to create a defensive copynof the list.n

DeveloperGuide: use labeled list for glossaryThe glossary uses literal blocks for formatting definitions, which looksnstrange because literal blocks are usually used for preformatted textnsuch as source code.nnInstead, let's use a labeled list, which has a formatting that is morenin line with a glossary definition list.nnConvert the paragraph anchors into inline anchors[1], so that the itemsnare joined into one single labeled list with two items, rather thannbeing chopped into two separate labeled lists with one item each.nn[1] See http://asciidoctor.org/docs/user-manual/#anchordef for thendifference between a paragraph anchor and an inline anchor.n

build.gradle: standardize dependency specifications code styleThere are different styles of specifying dependencies in thenbuild.gradle file, so let's standardize all of them into one singlenstyle.nnThis style is chosen as it makes the groupId, artifactId, and version ofnthe dependency obvious.nnRather than defining the dependency versions as project.ext properties,njust define them directly in the dependencies block so that thendependency version number is immediately obvious. build.gradle: remove `forkEvery = 1`Setting `forkEvery = 1` has the effect of restarting the Java processnfor every test class run. As the JVM takes a long time to start up, thisnends up making our test execution time unnecessarily long.nnAs there doesn't seem to be a reason for why forkEvery has to be set ton1, let's remove the setting. This will leave it at its default settingnof zero, which means don't restart the Java process at all.nnThis significantly speeds up test execution. e.g. On my box,n`./gradlew headless allTests` now takes only around a minute to run,ncompared to around 3 minutes before.n

docs: remove env-github outfilesuffix boilerplateMany of our adoc files have the following boilerplate:nnifdef::env-github,env-browser[:outfilesuffix: .adoc]nnThis boilerplate used to be required in order for inter-document crossnreferences to work when viewing the adoc files directly on GitHub. Thisnwas because GitHub errnously set the outfilesuffix as `.html` instead ofn`.adoc`, which resulted in broken links.nnHowever, as the asciidoctor user guide[1] states:nnThis configuration is no longer necessary on GitHub since GitHub nownsets the value of outfilesuffix to match the file extension of thensource file. DeveloperGuide, UserGuide: use full xrefstyleBy default, the cross-reference text when cross-referencing anothernsection, figure, table etc. will be the title of that section, figure,ntable etc.nnFor example, the following cross-reference in the DeveloperGuide:nn<<architecture>>nnwill be replaced with:nnArchitecturennwhich is the name of that section.nnHowever, in a printed or non-interactive medium, cross-referencenhyperlinks do not work. As such, it would be more useful to provide thensection/figure/table number as well, so that readers will be able tonquickly locate the reference target by its number, rather than needingnto manually find its name in the document.nnAs such, lets set the xrefstyle of the UserGuide and DeveloperGuide ton`full`. With this change, the <<architecture>> cross-reference would benreplaced with:nnSection 2.1, ArchitecturennAs the xrefstyle feature[1] was only introduced in asciidoctor 1.5.6[2],nwe'll need to upgrade our asciidoctor plugin as well.nn[1] http://asciidoctor.org/docs/user-manual/#customizing-the-cross-reference-textn[2] https://github.com/asciidoctor/asciidoctor/commit/8e80317dee56483e48a07451bff0cd14f0bfd59cn

DeveloperGuide, UserGuide: use cross references instead of manual linksThe UserGuide and DeveloperGuide contains many links to other sectionsnin the document. However, these links are written using the link: syntaxnrather than using the cross reference syntax.nnIn many cases, the link text simply repeats the title of the referencednsection. Such uses result in unnecessary verbosity, and are also fragilensince someone who modifies the title of the referenced section couldneasily forget to change the link text of links referencing that sectionnas well.nnLet's fix this by changing the links to use the cross reference syntaxninstead, which provide automatic link text, so we do not need to repeatnthe section titles.nnIf the anchor IDs of the referenced sections change, it would lead tondead links as well. As such, let's also give the referenced sectionsnexplicit anchor IDs to make sure they do not change.n

DeveloperGuide: use proper syntax for figure captionsThe DeveloperGuide manually numbers each figure.nnSuch manually numbering of figures is error prone and leads to a problemnwhere inserting a figure between two other figures causes a snowballneffect where all subsequent figure numbers needs to be updated, whichnpollutes the commit diff.nnAs such, let's switch to using asciidoctor's automatic figure numberingninstead, which kicks in when we switch to using the proper syntax fornfigure captions -- by defining the caption text as the title of thenblock image[1].nnAs a side benefit of using the figure caption syntax, we can now alsonuse the cross reference syntax to reference other figures, which willngive us the desired behavior of referencing that figure with the correctnfigure number.nnOne downside of this approach is that the automatic figure numbers arennot hierarchical, i.e. they just go 1, 2, 3... without taking thensection numbers into account. However, the upside of not having tonmanually update figure numbers is much more valuable.nn[1] http://asciidoctor.org/docs/user-manual/#imagesn

UiPart: allow callers to specify the scenegraph rootFXML files may wish to use the <fx:root> feature[1] where, rather thannthe FXML file specifying and creating the root object, a placeholdernroot is used instead which can then be specified when the FXML isnloaded. This is useful in situations where we wish to use a preexistingnobject as the root.nnHowever, UiPart doesn't provide a way for callers to specify the rootnobject, and thus the <fx:root> feature cannot be used.nnFix this by introducing UiPart(URL, T) and UiPart(String, T)nconstructors which are similar to UiPart(URL) and UiPart(String), butnallows callers to specify the root object to be used. This requires usnto extract out some utility methods to share common functionalitynbetween these constructors.nnThe next few commits will take advantage of this new feature.nn[1] https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/javafx/api/javafx/fxml/doc-files/introduction_to_fxml.html#custom_componentsn

SystemTestSetupHelper: use a new primary stage for each applicationBy default, with TestFX, the same primary stage is shared between allnsystem tests.nnThis could cause state leaks between tests. For example, if one systemntest adds an event filter to its primary stage, this event filter willnbe preserved throughout all the other system tests, causing incorrectnbehavior.nnWhile our application does not modify the primary stage in a way whichnbreaks tests if the primary stage is reused, we would be doing somentweaks to the code base in the next commit which would cause this tonhappen.nnAs such, let's preemptively fix this problem by creating a new primarynstage every time SystemTestSetupHelper#setupApplication(...) is called.nThis is done by modifying it to call:nnFxToolkit.registerStage(Stage::new);nnSince the primary stage created by FxToolkit.registerPrimaryStage()nisn't actually used in the system tests, let's fix up the javadocs innSystemTestSetupHelper to take account this new state of affairs.nnIn addition, let's rename SystemTestSetupHelper#initializeStage() tonSystemTestSetupHelper#initialize() since its main purpose now isn't toncreate the primary stage, but to call TestFX's initializationnroutines[1].nn[1] FxToolkit.registerPrimaryStage() will still need to be called evennthough the primary stage it creates is not used in tests.nThis is because, despite what its name implies, it actually doesnmuch more than just creating the primary stage: it sets up JavaFXnfor headless testing and prevents JavaFX from shutting down when thenlast stage is hidden.n

MainWindow: make the primary Stage the root objectReaders would expect the root object of the UiPart `MainWindow` to benits `Stage` window. However, this is not so. The root object ofn`MainWindow` is a `Region`, and the Stage and Scene which MainWindownmanages is sneakily handled inside its constructor.nnWhile this works, it does against the architecture of the UiPart system,nwhich dictates that the return value of UiPart#getRoot(), as well as thenroot node of the FXML file, should be the root object of the scene graphnwhich the UiPart manages. This derivation from the architecture maynconfuse readers.nnAt the same time, we can't directly specify a Stage as the root nodeninside the MainWindow.fxml file. This is because under the JavaFXnarchitecture, we should use the primary stage which is created by thenJavaFX framework, rather than constructing our own.nnFix this by using the <fx:root> feature of FXML file. This allows us tonspecify a javafx.stage.Stage as the root object of MainWindow.fxml,nwhile also allowing us to inject the primary stage object as the rootnat runtime when MainWindow is constructed.nnNote that with this change, MainWindow#setAccelerator(...) will nowninstall an event filter on the primary stage. This could be problematicnif the primary stage was somehow reused across applications, butnfortunately in the previous commit we have already taken care ofnensuring this is not possible.n

TestUtil#assertThrows(...): support checked exceptionsTestUtil#assertThrows(...) doesn't support functions which throw checkednexceptions. For example,nnTestUtil.assertThrows(IllegalValueException.class, () -> { throw new IllegalValueException(); });nnwould not compile, with the compiler complaining with:nnerror: unreported exception IllegalValueException; must be caught or declared to be thrownnnThis is because assertThrows(...) takes in a Runnable, whose run()nmethod does not have `throws Exception` declared.nnjava.util.concurrent.Callable<V>, on the other hand, looks like what wenwant, as it is a functional interface whose call() method hasn`throws Exception` declared. Unfortunately, due to how Java's genericsnwork, call() MUST return a value. This means we will need to tack on an`return null` at the end of our lambda bodies, which is too verbose. Notngood.nnAs such, let's define our own `VoidCallable` interface, and modifynassertThrows(...) to take it. Like Callable<V>, VoidCallable#call methodnhas `throws Exceptions` declared, so our lambdas passed tonassertThrows(...) can throw checked exceptions.  Unlike Callable<V>, itsncall() method doesn't need to return a return value, allowing us tonwrite succinct lambda expressions to pass to assertThrows(...).n

Move string trimming responsibility from Name to ParserUtil#parseName(String)Name's constructor modifies the input string by trimming leading andntrailing whitespace. However, given that the model component'snsole responsibility is to store data in memory, it shouldn't benmodifying any input. Rather, any munging of input should be done in thenparser layer.nnFix this by moving the string trimming logic from Name tonParserUtil#parseName(String).n

Move Name validation step from model to the parser and storage layersThe Name(String) constructor validates the passed in name String,nthrowing a checked IllegalValueException error if the input failsnvalidation.nnHowever, according to our architecture, the model layer should only benconcerned with the storage of data in memory. Any data which reaches thenmodel layer should have already been validated. As such, if for anynreason the input name String fails validation in the model layer, it isnmost likely a programmer error, and a runtime exception should thus benthrown instead.nnFix this by moving the input validation step, and the throwing of thenchecked IllegalValueException, from the Name constructor to the parsernlayer and storage layers. The Name constructor will instead use thencheckArgument(...) helper function to verify the valid namenprecondition.nnThanks to this fix, as Name's constructor does not throw checkednexceptions any more, we can remove a try/catch block from PersonBuildernas well (otherwise the code won't compile).n

build.gradle: teach test tasks to work togetherThe allTests, nonGuiTests, guiTests tasks are implemented as separatentasks which are unaware of whether each other is being run. This leadsnto strange behavior such as the following command which runs some testsnmultiple times:nn./gradlew allTests nonGuiTests guiTestsnnThese tasks are also not integrated with the `test` task, which isnprovided by default by the `java` plugin. This is the de facto task fornrunning tests, and is run by default by other commonly-used tasks suchnas `./gradlew check` and `./gradlew build`.nnFix this by making all of these tasks aware of each other. The `test`ntask is configured to be *the* task that runs the tests, while thennonGuiTests and guiTests tasks are converted to dummy tasks which justnserve to inform the `test` task of whether to run the GUI tests or not.nnEverything works as normal, except that nown`./gradlew allTests nonGuiTests guiTests` will have the expected resultnof running all tests only once. Other task combinations, such asn`./gradlew headless test` and `./gradlew headless check` now also haventhe correct behavior of running tests in headless mode.n

XmlSerializableAddressBook: add toModelType() methodXmlSerializableAddressBook does not have a method to convert itself tonan AddressBook object. It implements ReadOnlyAddressBook and hasngetPersonList() and getTagList() methods, which the caller uses toncreate an AddressBook object.nnBy implementing ReadOnlyAddressBook, the overridden getPersonList()nand getTagList() methods are unable to throw IllegalValueException tonhigher level components for error handling if there's errors in then.xml save file.nnAs part of removing XmlSerializableAddressBook implementation ofnReadOnlyAddressBook, let's add a toModelType() method to convertnthe XmlSerializableAddressBook to the model's AddressBook object.nnIn order to test that the toModelType() method throwsnIllegalValueException, we first need to construct an invalidnXmlAdaptedPerson or XmlAdaptedTag. However, XmlSerializableAddressBookncan only add XmlAdaptedPerson and XmlAdaptedTag to itself throughnit's constructor, which takes a ReadOnlyAddressBook. The model Person'snobject fields prevent us from assigning illegal values throughnexecution of the app. Thus, the only way we can assign XmlAdaptedPersonnor XmlAdaptedTag with illegal values to XmlSerializableAddressBook isnthrough creating a .xml file with these illegal values, and readingnthe .xml file using XmlUtil#getDataFromFile(File, Class).n

HelpWindow: modify HelpWindow#show() to use Stage#show()opened by typing help in the command box. For instance, the command box ndoes not display the result message of subsequent commands. However, nthis does not occur when opening the help window by pressing F1 or npressing help from the help menu. nnThis occurs due to a combination of using the default Dispatcher used nby the Guava EventBus system, Dispatcher#perThreadDispatchQueue(), nalong with calling Stage#showAndWait(). Calling Stage#showAndWait(), nstarts a nested event loop to handle subsequent JavaFX events. However, nthe default Dispatcher used by the EventBus does not allow nested ncallback invocations, and instead queues them to be invoked after the ncurrent invoked callback, the MainWindow#handleShowHelpEvent() ncompletes. As such, EventBus events are queued up in the meantime nresulting in the subscribers of these events having to wait until the nnested event loop is terminated (i.e. when the callback completes, nafter the help window is closed.) And so, the UI components will only nreceive these events and therefore update after the help window is nclosed.nnHowever, in the case of pressing F1 or pressing help from the help menu, nMainWindow#handleHelp() is called immediately without posting thenMainWindow#handleShowHelpEvent(). Since this event never enters the nEventBus's queue, the nested event loop started by Stage#showAndWait() ndoes not block it and subsequent EventBus events get dispatched as nusual.nnLet's replace Stage#showAndWait() with Stage#show(), so nthat there will be no entering of a nested loop and hence no blockage nof the Guava EventBus system.nnLikewise, this could be fixed by using the Dispatcher#immediate() ndispatcher instead of the default dispatcher used by the Guava EventBus nsystem. However, replacing Stage#showAndWait() with Stage#show() is nmore suitable in this case as it is sufficient to show the help window ninstead of starting a nested event loop to handle subsequent JavaFX nevents while waiting for the help window to be closed.nnJavaFX documentation for Stage:nhttps://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/javafx/api/javafx/stage/Stage.htmlnnCode and documentation for the Guava Dispatcher:nhttps://github.com/google/guava/blob/master/guava/src/com/google/common/eventbus/Dispatcher.javannMore information on the Guava EventBus system:nhttps://github.com/google/guava/wiki/EventBusExplained

MainWindow.fxml: update onCloseRequest event to call handleExit()The MainWindow does not have an event handler to handle externalnrequests (such as the close button or through the taskbar) to closenthe MainWindow.nnThis may cause the app to not close properly since MainApp#stop() isnnot called as the ExitAppRequestEvent is not raised. MainApp#stop() isnthe method used to call Platform#exit() and System#exit(int) whichncloses our app and all remaining open windows. Thus, if MainApp#stop()nis not called, the app may continue to run even after the MainWindow isnclosed, causing existing HelpWindows to remain open even when the usernexpects the app to stop.nnAccording to the life-cycle section in the documentation on JavaFXnApplication[1], the app will only finish and call MainApp#stop() whennthe app either calls Platform#exit() or when the last window has beennclosed. Thus, should there be any HelpWindows still opened, the appnwill continue running, causing those HelpWindows to remain open.nnLet's add an event handler for the onCloseRequest event in the root ofnMainWindow.fxml. This event will call MainWindow#handleExit(), whichnraises an ExitAppRequestEvent, when there is an external request tonclose the app.nnEmptyMainWindowHandle does not contain a close button, thus to test ifnan ExitAppRequestEvent was raised, we fire anWindowEvent#WINDOW_CLOSE_REQUEST event which will trigger thenonCloseRequest event.nn[1] JavaFx documentation for Application:nhttps://docs.oracle.com/javafx/2/api/javafx/application/Application.htmln

build.gradle: upgrade to newest versionThe version of Gradle we are using is 2.12.nnThis version of Gradle does not support projects that are usingnJava 9 [1]; an error of Could not determine java version fromn'9.0.4' occurs.nnLet's upgrade the version of Gradle to the newest version.nn[1]: https://blog.gradle.org/java-9-support-updaten

build.gradle: upgrade to use Java 9The project currently runs on Java 8.nnWe should ensure compatibility with the latest public version as soonnas it is out.nnLet's upgrade the project to run on Java 9 and update the documentationnaccordingly.nnSome of the properties in gradle.properties are no longer supported.nAs PermGen has been replaced with Metaspace, -XX:MaxPermSize=size hasnceased support [1] and has been replaced with -XX:MaxMetaspaceSize [2].nAlso, -XX:CMSPermGenSweepingEnabled has been superseded byn-XX:+CMSClassUnloadingEnabled and removed in JDK 9 [3][4].n-XX:+CMSClassUnloadingEnabled however, is useless now. When PermGen wasnused previously, this command line argument ensured that PermGen wasngarbage collected [5]. However, Metaspace is automatically garbagencollected [6], therefore there's no replacement for this argument.nLet's remove or update these properties accordingly.nnTravis & AppVeyor are building the project using JDK 8. Since we arennow running on Java 9, let's update them to build the project usingnJDK 9.nnTo run tests using TestFX on Java 9, we have to update the dependenciesnin build.gradle. Let's update it according to TestFX'sndocumentation [7].nnJava 9 introduces a module system, causing internal packages such asnjavax.* and com.sun.* packages to be inaccessible. As our project usesnthese packages, our code is no longer compilable. Let's updatenbuild.gradle to import these modules.nn[1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/9/migrate/toc.htmn[2]: http://java-latte.blogspot.sg/2014/03/metaspace-in-java-8.htmln[3]: http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/9-removed-features-3745614.htmln[4]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3717937/cmspermgensweepingenabled-vs-cmsclassunloadingenabledn[5]: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3334911/what-does-jvm-flag-cmsclassunloadingenabled-actually-don[6]: http://kkgulati.blogspot.sg/2014/09/java-8-memory-model-metaspace.htmln[7]: https://github.com/TestFX/TestFX#java-9n

Gradle: upgrade to JUnit5Gradle uses JUnit 4.12 for testing which is an older version of JUnit.nnLet's upgrade to JUnit 5. To use JUnit 5, we need to add in additionalndependencies junit-jupiter-api and junit-jupiter-engine.nJunit-jupiter-engine is used to execute the JUnit 5 tests duringnruntime, while junit-jupiter-api provides the api required for writingntests. Also, we need to use JUnit Platform, which is how Gradlenenables JUnit to run tests using its engine.nnJUnit 5 has a few differences with JUnit 4, which means the tests willnneed to be changed to run on the JUnit 5 engine. Some examples ofndifferences between JUnit5 and JUnit4 tests:n1. Different imports. (e.g. org.junit.jupiter.api.Test instead ofnorg.junit.Test)n2. Test cannot be used for specifying expectations. We use this tonspecify timeout in `PersonListPanelTest`. Instead we should now usenassertTimeoutPreemptivelyn3. @Before is renamed to @BeforeEachn4. @After is renamed to @AfterEachn5. @BeforeClass is renamed to @BeforeAlln6. @AfterClass is renamed to @AfterAlln7. We can group assertions together using assertAlln8. @Rule and @ClassRule are not used in JUnit5. Instead, we need ton@ExtendWith, which generally requires creating an extension class.nnLet's enable legacy support for JUnit 4 tests. By addingnjunit-vintage-engine as a dependency, JUnit 4 tests can be runnnormally.n

Refactor codebase to use java.nio.file for file/path handlingString operations are used for the construction of file paths. Also,nmany APIs in the codebase take in String arguments as file paths.nnThis method of file/path handling is error prone as creating paths usingnstring concatenation can lead to the creation of invalid paths.nFurthermore, checking if two paths resolve to the same file using stringnequality is incorrect as it only tests if the strings are equal.nnLet's refactor the codebase to use java.nio.file for file/pathnhandling as it provides a safe and platform-independent way tonperform operations on paths and properly separate the concerns ofnparsing/stringifying paths and manipulating paths.nnMore information on why String operations are error-prone:nhttp://twistedoakstudios.com/blog/Post4872_dont-treat-paths-like-strings

HelpWindowTest: fix failing test in non-headless modeHelpWindowTest#focus_helpWindowNotFocused_focused() asserts that thenHelpWindow is not in focus when it is first shown, and then assertsnthat the HelpWindow comes into focus after calling HelpWindow#focus().nnWhen tests are run in non-headless mode, the HelpWindow will be innfocus when it is first shown, thus rendering our first assumption falsenand causing the test to fail.nnLet's update the test to focus on another TestFx Stage, which willnremove focus from the HelpWindow when it is first shown, ensuring thatnthe initial assumption is true.n

HelpWindowTest: skip test with buggy behavior in headless modeHelpWindowTest#focus_helpWindowNotFocused_focused test checksnwhether calling HelpWindow#focus() will bring the HelpWindow to focus.nNormally, when HelpWindow#show() is called, the HelpWindow'snStage should automatically be in focus.nnHowever, when tests are run in headless mode, the HelpWindow innHelpWindowTest#focus_helpWindowNotFocused_focused test does notnautomatically come into focus after it is shown.nnThis is due to HelpWindowStage in setUp() setting the HelpWindow'snScene to itself. According to the JavaFx docs fornWindow#setScene(Scene)[1], a Scene can only be on one Stage at a time,nand setting a Scene on a different Stage will cause the old Stage tonlose the reference. As a result, the HelpWindow's Stage will not have anreference to any Scene, resulting in the HelpWindow's Stage not comingninto focus automatically, due to a bug with Monocle's headless mode.nnLet's skip HelpWindowTest#focus_helpWindowNotFocused_focused test whenntests are run in headless mode as it is relying on buggy behavior.nn[1]: JavaFx docs for Window#setScene(Scene):nhttps://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/javafx/api/javafx/stage/Window.html#setScene-javafx.scene.Scene-n

Fix stalling HelpWindowTestWhen running `gradlew headless allTests`, gradle will sometimes stall onnHelpWindowTest.nnWhile we do not know the exact cause of this stalling, we have narrowednit down to the following conditions[1] which must all be present for thenstalling to occur:nn  1. The test must be running in headless mode.nn  2. There must be two stages created, one with a WebView, and one withn no scene.nn  3. Both stages must be shown.nnSince it is pretty difficult and time-consuming to debug and find outnthe exact cause of this stalling, let's fix this issue by removing onenof its trigger conditions.nn(1) obviously cannot be removed, since we want headless testing to worknon our code. For (2), the HelpWindow needs to have a WebView to show thenuser guide, and so we can't remove the WebView.nnBut really, stepping back a bit, we can see that the whole test setupnwhich leads to (2) and (3) being present in the first place is prettynstrange:nn// (a)nguiRobot.interact(() -> helpWindow = new HelpWindow());n// (b)nStage helpWindowStage = FxToolkit.setupStage((stage) -> stage.setScene(helpWindow.getRoot().getScene()));n// (c)nFxToolkit.showStage();nhelpWindowHandle = new HelpWindowHandle(helpWindowStage);n[...]n// (d)nguiRobot.interact(helpWindow::show);nnIn (a), we create an instance of HelpWindow, which has its own Stagenwhich can be retrieved with HelpWindow#getRoot().nnHowever, in (b) we transfer the HelpWindow's scene to the TestFX'snprimary stage, leaving the helpWindow with no scene. But: there is nonreason to use the TestFX's registered primary stage when HelpWindownalready has its own Stage.nnAnd in (c), we show the TestFX primary stage, and then later in (d) wenshow the helpWindow. However, given that helpWindow does not have anscene and is thus not showing anything, it would be deceptive to use itnfor tests which are meant to verify that the application worksncorrectly.nnAs such, let's fix the stalling by fixing the root of the problem: thenbogus test setup. Rather than having two stages, let's just usenHelpWindow's stage directly for all tests, and register it as the TestFXnprimary stage using FxToolkit#registerStage(...). This has the effect ofnremoving trigger conditions (2) and (3), since we now only have onenStage, thus fixing the stalling.nnNOTE: Even with this fix, focus_helpWindowNotFocused_focused() stillncannot be run in headless mode, although for a different reason comparednto when this skip was introduced in 2cf5b98 (HelpWindowTest: skip testnwith buggy behavior in headless mode, 2018-04-21). Now, this test willnfail due to a different JavaFX bug[2]. Clarify this by adding commentsnexplaining why the test is skipped in headless mode.nn---n[1] Minimal reproducer for the stalling:nnpackage seedu.address.ui;nnimport org.junit.Test;nimport org.testfx.api.FxRobot;nimport org.testfx.api.FxToolkit;nnimport javafx.scene.Scene;nimport javafx.scene.web.WebView;nimport javafx.stage.Stage;nnpublic class HelpWindowTest {n@Testnpublic void test() throws Exception {nFxToolkit.registerPrimaryStage();nFxRobot fxRobot = new FxRobot();nfxRobot.interact(() -> {nStage stage1 = new Stage();nstage1.setScene(new Scene(new WebView()));nStage stage2 = new Stage();nn// Order in which stages are shown does not matternstage1.show();nstage2.show();n});nn// May or may not stall here depending on your lucknfxRobot.interact(() -> {});n}n}nn[2] https://github.com/javafxports/openjdk-jfx/issues/50n

Gradle wrapper: upgrade to Gradle 4.8.1With JDK 10, `./gradlew allTest` fails to run tests, instead spewing outnthe following errors on the console:nnException in thread main java.lang.reflect.InvocationTargetExceptionnat java.base/jdk.internal.reflect.NativeMethodAccessorImpl.invoke0(Native Method)nat java.base/jdk.internal.reflect.NativeMethodAccessorImpl.invoke(NativeMethodAccessorImpl.java:62)nat java.base/jdk.internal.reflect.DelegatingMethodAccessorImpl.invoke(DelegatingMethodAccessorImpl.java:43)nat java.base/java.lang.reflect.Method.invoke(Method.java:564)nat java.instrument/sun.instrument.InstrumentationImpl.loadClassAndStartAgent(InstrumentationImpl.java:510)nFATAL ERROR in native method: processing of -javaagent failednat java.instrument/sun.instrument.InstrumentationImpl.loadClassAndCallPremain(InstrumentationImpl.java:522)nCaused by: java.lang.RuntimeException: Class java/lang/UnknownError could not be instrumented.nat org.jacoco.agent.rt.internal_290345e.core.runtime.ModifiedSystemClassRuntime.createFor(ModifiedSystemClassRuntime.java:139)nat org.jacoco.agent.rt.internal_290345e.core.runtime.ModifiedSystemClassRuntime.createFor(ModifiedSystemClassRuntime.java:100)nat org.jacoco.agent.rt.internal_290345e.PreMain.createRuntime(PreMain.java:55)nat org.jacoco.agent.rt.internal_290345e.PreMain.premain(PreMain.java:47)n... 6 morenCaused by: java.lang.NoSuchFieldException: $jacocoAccessnat java.base/java.lang.Class.getField(Class.java:1958)nat org.jacoco.agent.rt.internal_290345e.core.runtime.ModifiedSystemClassRuntime.createFor(ModifiedSystemClassRuntime.java:137)n... 9 morenn... and so forthnnAccording to a PR[1] on the JaCoCo's issue tracker, this occurs becausenClasses of JDK 10 EA b35 use a new classfile version number and sonJaCoCo Agent 0.7.9 as well as agent from current build of master branchnfail to start. This has been fixed as of JaCoCo 0.8.1, which alsonhappens to be the latest release.nnWe do not explicitly specify the version JaCoCo to use in ournbuild.gradle file, and so the `jacoco` gradle plugin just uses itsndefault, which happens to be 0.8.0[2] on Gradle 4.6 (the version we arenusing). This version of JaCoCo still has this bug, and so we get thesenerrors.nnFix this by upgrading to the latest version of Gradle (4.8.1). SincenGradle 4.7[3] the default JaCoCo plugin has been upgraded to versionn0.8.1, and so upgrading to the latest version of Gradle will fix thisnproblem and allow us to run tests on JDK 10.nnThe Gradle wrapper upgrade was performed by running the command:nn./gradlew wrapper --gradle-version 4.8.1nnand then converting the line endings of gradlew.bat to unix to satisfynour travis line ending checks.nnAlso, update any references to the Gradle version we are using in thencode base to 4.8.1.nn[1] https://github.com/jacoco/jacoco/pull/629n[2] https://github.com/gradle/gradle/commit/8a09484f4166737cf60ea945409d49340ffb8ae3n[3] https://docs.gradle.org/4.7/release-notes.html#default-jacoco-version-upgraded-to-0.8.1n

build.gradle: asciidoctor: specify template_dirsIn the upcoming commits, we will be adding a navigation bar to thenSE-EDU website using asciidoctor's template mechanism[1].nnIn preparation of that, let's teach the asciidoctor gradle plugin tonlook for our template files inside the docs/templates/ directory bynspecifying the template_dirs option.nnLikewise, to guarantee correctness of the build, teach Gradle to rebuildnour documentation if any of the template files change by specifying thentemplate files as task inputs[2].nn[1] https://asciidoctor.org/docs/user-manual/#provide-custom-templatesn[2] https://docs.gradle.org/4.8.1/userguide/more_about_tasks.html#sec:runtime_api_for_adhocn

docs/templates: import asciidoctor reference templateWe are trying to implement a navigation bar in the SE-EDU website usingnasciidoctor's template mechanism[1].nnAsciidoctor's template mechanism works by allowing template developersnto override the rendering of certain blocks in asciidoctor's syntaxntree. For our case, if we want to add a navigation bar to the top of thenpage, we will need to override asciidoctor's `document` block handling.nnThe problem is: the rendering logic for the document block itself isnquite coarse -- covering everything from the header <meta> and <script>ntags to the footer's last updated text. If we just want to add annavigation bar without changing the rest of the document's output, wenwill need to re-implement a large part of asciidoctor's HTML5 backend.nnFortunately, the asciidoctor-backends[2] repository has done most of thenhard work for us -- it features complete re-implementation of templatesnthat mirror asciidoctor's default HTML5 output. By using these templatesnas a base, we can then make minimal changes on top to get our navigationnbar.nnThe asciidoctor-backends repo has templates for three different templatenengines: ERB, HAML and Slim. All three template engines are supported bynthe asciidoctor Gradle plugin, since AsciidoctorJ bundles them insidenits JAR file[3].nnFollowing the recommendation of asciidoctor's project lead[4], let's usenthe Slim backend.nnImport the necessary template files, contained within the slim/html5/ndirectory, from the latest commitn(8ffcad1f9194fe2638f673aea7e41ed28c654800) of the asciidoctor-backendsnrepo.nnSince we only need to modify the handling of the `document` block, wenjust need to import `document.html.slim`, as well as its dependencies.nn[1] https://asciidoctor.org/docs/user-manual/#provide-custom-templatesnn[2] https://github.com/asciidoctor/asciidoctor-backendsnn[3] https://github.com/asciidoctor/asciidoctorj#project-layoutnnAlso bundles optional RubyGems needed at runtime, such as coderay,ntile, haml and slim.nn[4] https://github.com/asciidoctor/asciidoctor-backends/issues/118#issuecomment-99609554nnWe should point out that ERB is complex and that, in ournexperience, the templates were exceptionally hard to maintain whenndone in ERB. In contrast, the templates are simple and clear whenndone in Slim and we have convenient facilities for simplifying thentemplates further with utility methods. Slim is a smarternengineering choice.n

docs/templates/helpers.rb: remove unused codeIn the previous commit, we imported helpers.rb, as well as otherntemplate files, from the asciidoctor-backends[1] repo.nnHowever, as we did not import all of the template files, some of thencode in helpers.rb is unused.nnThe unused code is an unnecessary maintenance and readability burden, sonlet's remove them.nn[1] https://github.com/asciidoctor/asciidoctor-backends/tree/master/slim/html5n

docs/templates: remind devs to restart the gradle daemonFor the purpose of speed, the asciidoctor gradle plugin will reuse thenasciidoctor instance to avoid reinstantiating the jruby runtime[1].nnThis has the effect of keeping the old template files in memory, meaningnthat if the template files are modified while the gradle daemon isnrunning, the changes won't be reflected in the running gradle daemon.nThe documentation will still use the old template even when then`asciidoctor` task is rerun.nnThis optimization is however, still beneficial: developers are morenlikely to edit the documentation adoc files compared to modifying thentemplate files. As such, they will benefit from the speed increasengained from keeping the template files in memory. Thus, we will not makenany attempt to work around this.nnInstead, let's add a comment to the top of every template file,nreminding developers that if they wish for their changes to the templatenfiles to be reflected in the generated HTML files, they will need tonrestart the Gradle daemon.nn[1] https://github.com/asciidoctor/asciidoctor-gradle-plugin/commit/0b9d614fb10fcf79747588e0a8257fca5b96033an
