docs: add site navigation barTo give readers a more cohesive browsing experience, let's add annavigation bar to the top of every page.nnThis navigation bar will remind readers the name of the website they arenbrowsing (AddressBook-Level4), and will provide convenient links tonfrequently-used documents, such as the User Guide and Developer Guide.nnImplement this navigation bar using the templating mechanism that wenhave set up over the past few commits, and document it in the DevelopernGuide.nnSome important concerns that we need to handle are:nn 1. Given that AddressBook-Level4 is meant to be used by students as anbase to build their own products, which may or may not be an addressnbook app, we should be able to easily specify the site name that isndisplayed in the navigation bar.nnSolution: Teach the navigation bar to use the asciidoc attributen`site-name` as the site name.nn 2. Not all documents may wish to have a navigation bar displayed at thentop of their page.nnSolution: Teach the navigation bar to check if the asciidocnattribute `no-site-header` is set. If it is, then we don't rendernthe navigation bar.nn 3. The rendered documentation should be browsable locally. Thus, linksnin the navigation bar must be relative, and the proper relativenlinks must be generated no matter how deep the documentationndirectory tree is.nnSolution: Introduce an asciidoc attribute `site-root`, which shouldnstore the absolute path of the root documentation directory. Innother words, it should be the same as the `sourceDir` specified innbuild.gradle. This is used to workaround the fact that thenasciidoctor gradle plugin only passes in individual filenames, andnnot the sourceDir, to asciidoctor.nnThe navigation bar can then compare the current directory with then`site-root` directory, and use it to generate the correct relativenpaths.nn 4. It looks nicer if the item that the reader is currently browsing isnhighlighted in the navigation bar. e.g. If the current page is thenDeveloper Guide, the Developer Guide item will be highlighted innthe navigation bar.nnThis requirement is complicated by the fact that the DevelopernGuide actually comprises of many documents: UsingGradle, UsingnTravis, UsingAppVeyor etc.nnSolution: Teach the navigation bar to examine the `site-section`nattribute of the document, and highlight the appropriate navigationnitem.nn 5. The templating mechanism is extremely advanced and requires somenknowledge of Ruby and Asciidoctor's API. Downstream projects maynmodify the template file, break it, and then file an issue expectingnsupport from us.nnSolution: Explicitly state in the Developer Guide that we do notnprovide support for modified template files. If downstream projectsnbreak the files, they get to keep the pieces.nnThanks to the additional configuration attributes that we have added,ndownstream projects will need to do more configuration to tweak thendocumentation settings to match their fork. Update the developer guidento mention this.n

System Tests: remove model verification checksWhenever System Tests asserts if a command is executed correctly,nthere will be a verification to check that the internalncomponents, such as the model, is correct.nnAs System Tests are categorised as black box testing, it isn'tnnecessary to verify the internal components, such as the model.nnLet's remove model verification checks for System Tests.n

Add VersionedAddressBook ClassThe undo/redo mechanism uses an UndoRedoStack stored in thenLogicManager, which uses 2 stacks to store executed and undonenUndoableCommands. The UndoableCommands stores the previousAddressBooknstate before execution, which is used to restore the AddressBook statenduring an undo command.nnThis results in unnecessary coupling between the UndoableCommandn(within the Logic Layer) and AddressBook (within the Model Layer).nnLet's add a new class, VersionedAddressBook which extends AddressBooknand shift the undo redo machanism from UndoRedoStack in LogicManagernto VersionedAddressBook in ModelManager. This VersionedAddressBooknclass will use a list to keep track of the different versions ofnAddressBook by maintaining a list of AddressBook States.nnSince VersionedAddressBook will store all the AddressBook states,nUndoableCommand will no longer need to store thenpreviousAddressBookState in itself.n

Remove UndoRedoStack classThe undo/redo mechanism previously uses UndoRedoStack which storesnUndoableCommands.nnSince the undo/redo mechanism has switched from using UndoRedoStack tonVersionedAddressBook, UndoRedoStack is no longer used. As such, itnshould be removed for code quality purposes.nnLet's remove UndoRedoStack class and its corresponding tests.n

Remove UndoableCommand classUndoableCommand was previously used to undo and redo commands throughnits UndoableCommand#undo() and UndoableCommand#redo() methodnrespectively.nnThe undo/redo mechanism now uses an VersionedAddressBook which uses anlist to keep track of the AddressBook's history. As such there is nonlonger a need for UndoableCommand class, and it should be removed forncode quality purposes.nnLet's remove UndoableCommand class and its corresponding tests, asnwell as making all commands extend from Command class instead.nnFollowing this change, UndoableCommand#preprocessUndoableCommand() isnno longer called when it is required for commands such as DeleteCommandnand EditCommand. The intention of havingnUndoableCommand#preprocessUndoableCommand() was to resolve an issue[1]nin our app.nnSince this issue is also resolved here by moving the undo/redonmechanism from UndoRedoStack to VersionedAddressBook which tracksnAddressBook states instead of UndoableCommands, there is no longer anneed for a separate method to preprocess the commands.nnLet's inline DeleteCommand#preprocessUndoableCommand() intonDeleteCommand#execute() and EditCommand#preprocessUndoableCommand()ninto EditCommand#execute().nn[1] Issue with undo/redo and modifications to filtered lists:nhttps://github.com/se-edu/addressbook-level4/issues/737n

.gitattributes: treat all *.pdf files as binarySome students may wish to commit PDF files into their downstream repos.nnThe PDF file format[1] is _mostly_ text-like. As such, it is likely thatnthe first 8000 bytes of any PDF file will _not_ contain a NUL byte,nleading Git to treat the PDF file as a text file[2].nnIn AddressBook-Level4, our Travis `run-checks` scripts requires all textnfiles, as determined by Git, to fulfill certain requirements such asnonly having LF line endings and not having any trailing whitespace.nnHowever, PDF files, although usually determined by Git to be text files,nmay not actually be _fully_ text. Particularly, PDF files may containnembedded binary streams which contain arbitrary binary data.nnThis arbitrary binary data can cause PDF files to fail our Travisn`run-checks` scripts.nnGiven that PDFs _can_ contain binary data, it would thus make more sensento treat the entire file as binary. This both allows them to pass ourn`run-checks` scripts, as well as to prevent Git from givingnnot-very-useful text diffs when the PDF files are modified.nnAs such, let's tell Git to treat all *.pdf files as binary.nn[1] https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PDF#File_structuren[2] https://github.com/git/git/blob/ffc6fa0e396238de3a30623912980263b4f283ab/xdiff-interface.c#L201-L207n

Remove use of `junit.framework` packageThere are certain places in our code base where we use classes from then`junit.framework` package.nnThe `junit.framework` package exists for backwards-compatibility withnJUnit 3[1]. We are not a legacy code base stuck on JUnit 3, thus wenshould use the JUnit 4 API.nnReplace uses of the `junit.framework` package with the JUnit 4 APInequivalents, namely:nn * Rather than using `junit.framework.TestCase.assertNotNull`, use then   JUnit 4 API's `org.junit.Assert.assertNotNull`[2].nn * Rather than using `junit.framework.AssertionFailedError`, usen   `java.lang.AssertionError` instead, since that is what is thrown byn   the JUnit 4 API on assertion failures.nn[1] From the package-info.java of `junit.framework` atnhttps://github.com/junit-team/junit4/blob/02c328028b4d32c15bbf0becc9838e54ecbafcbf/src/main/java/junit/framework/package-info.java#L2nnProvides JUnit v3.x core classesnn[2] https://stackoverflow.com/a/291074nnJUnit 3.X: junit.framework.Assertnn JUnit 4.X: org.junit.Assertnn Prefer the newest one, especially when running JDK5 and higher withn annotation support.n

Use chained exceptions consistently throughout the code baseIn some places of our code, we respond to an exception by throwingnanother exception.nnIn such a situation, it is good practice to _chain_ the exceptions bynpassing the initial exception as a `cause` to the next exception. Thisnis because it provides more information to higher-level exceptionnhandlers, allowing them to e.g. provide more meaningful stack tracesnthat show how the exception is handled and transformed as it isnpropagated through the call stack.nnHowever, certain places in our code base do not use exception chainingnwhen they could. These were discovered by grepping the code base forn`bthrowb` and seeing if any of the thrown exceptions fit the criteriandescribed above.nnLet's fix them to use chained exceptions.nnSee https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/essential/exceptions/chained.htmlnfor more information on chained exceptions.n

Replace uses of `org.junit.Assert.fail` with `throw new AssertionError(...)`The source code of `org.junit.Assert.fail(String)` is[1]:nnpublic static void fail(String message) {nif (message == null) {nthrow new AssertionError();n}nthrow new AssertionError(message);n}nnwhere `AssertionError` is our favorite `java.lang.AssertionError`.nnIn other words, calling `fail(String)` is no different from writingn`throw new AssertionError(...)`.nnThe latter has a further benefit, though -- it informs the Java compilernthat the code path terminates at that point. This is useful when we areninside a function that has a non-void return type -- if we usedn`fail(String)`, we will still need to `return` a dummy value at the endnto satisfy the compiler, whereas if we usedn`throw new AssertionError(...)` we do not need to do that.nnSo, let's use `throw new AssertionError(...)` consistently throughoutnthe code base.nn[1] https://github.com/junit-team/junit4/blob/02c328028b4d32c15bbf0becc9838e54ecbafcbf/src/main/java/org/junit/Assert.java#L85-L90n

ParserUtil: remove `Optional` variants of parse methodsAs the comment[1] at the top of ParserUtil says, methods that taken`Optional` as a parameter are bad.nnSo, let's remove them.nn(It could be argued that leaving these methods in the code base couldnserve as an example for students of what not to do, but really, (1) thennumber of things that are forbidden under best practice is quitennumerous, and trying to add an example of every single one of them innour code base would just lead to an annoyingly smelly code base, and (2)nstudents will need to spend time cleaning up all of these negativenexamples, which is an unnecessary burden. These things would be betterndocumented in style guides.)nn[1] Comment added in 84d6516f ([#557] ParserUtil: Update header commentsnon Optional usage (#558), 2017-07-18)n

model: make DuplicatePersonException a RuntimeExceptionDuplicatePersonException is a checked exception. It is thrown by methodsnsuch as `UniquePersonList#add(Person)`,n`UniquePersonList#setPerson(Person, Person)` etc. to signify thatncertain preconditions were not met -- namely that the operation wouldncause the no duplicate persons in address book/UniquePersonListnconstraint to be violated.nnUsing checked exceptions for such a purpose is slightly useful in thatnit will force callers to handle the case where the above preconditionsnare not met, such as when the methods are called with invalid userninput.nnHowever, it imposes a HUGE cost on callers where the preconditions arenalready known to be met (e.g. in test code, or when the user input hasnalready been validated before hand). In such a case, callers are forcednto add try-catch blocks around the method call even if they know thatnthe exception will never be thrown, bloating up the code. It is alsonimpossible to test the catch blocks as well since correct code willnensure that the precondition holds and thus the exception will never benthrown, leading to reduced code coverage.nnChecked exceptions also don't work very well with the Java Streams API,nsince the API doesn't accept lambdas which could throw checkednexceptions.nnIn AB-4, the amount of code which benefits fromnDuplicatePersonException being a checked exception is much smaller thannthe amount of code which is negatively impacted.nnAs such, let's make the tradeoff in the other direction, by makingnDuplicatePersonException a RuntimeException. New callers _could_ forgetnto check that the preconditions hold before calling the methods innquestion (although test cases should catch that), but this is balancednout by the huge benefit of having more concise and testable code.n

model: make PersonNotFoundException a RuntimeExceptionPersonNotFoundException is a checked exception. It is thrown by methodsnsuch as `UniquePersonList#remove(Person)`,n`UniquePersonList#setPerson(Person, Person)` etc. to signify thatncertain preconditions were not met -- namely that the person provided tonthose methods does not exist in the address book/UniquePersonList.nnUsing checked exceptions for such a purpose is slightly useful in thatnit will force callers to handle the case where the above preconditionsnare not met, such as when the methods are called with invalid userninput.nnHowever, it imposes a HUGE cost on callers where the preconditions arenalready known to be met (e.g. in test code, or when the user input hasnalready been validated before hand). In such a case, callers are forcednto add try-catch blocks around the method call even if they know thatnthe exception will never be thrown, bloating up the code. It is alsonimpossible to test the catch blocks as well since correct code willnensure that the precondition holds and thus the exception will never benthrown, leading to reduced code coverage.nnChecked exceptions also don't work very well with the Java Streams API,nsince the API doesn't accept lambdas which could throw checkednexceptions.nnIn AB-4, the amount of code which benefits from PersonNotFoundExceptionnbeing a checked exception is much smaller than the amount of code whichnis negatively impacted.nnAs such, let's make the tradeoff in the other direction, by makingnPersonNotFoundException a RuntimeException. New callers _could_ forgetnto check that the preconditions hold before calling the methods innquestion (although test cases should catch that), but this is balancednout by the huge benefit of having more concise and testable code.n

Command tests: verify CommandHistory as wellWhen executing a command, LogicManager will pass its CommandHistory tonthe command being executed.nnWhile commands can examine the CommandHistory, they should not modifynit. However, our command tests (in `seedu.address.logic.commands`) donnot verify the CommandHistory at all.nnLet's teach them to verify the CommandHistory. This is done by teachingnCommandTestUtil.assertCommandSuccess(...) andnCommandTestUtil.assertCommandFailure(...) to verify that thenCommandHistory is not modified.nnWe also need to implement CommandHistory#equals(Object), otherwisenassertEquals(...) will not work with it.n

Command: combine setData(...) and execute() togetherTo execute a command, (e.g. AddCommand), we need tonn  1. Construct it:nn AddCommand addCommand = new AddCommand(person);nn  2. Bind the model and command history to it:nn addCommand.setData(model, commandHistory);nn  3. And then execute it:nn addCommand.execute();nnHowever, there is no reason why step (2) and step (3) must be separate,nwhen it could just be:nnaddCommand.execute(model, commandHistory);nnIn fact, it causes more trouble:nn  * Since the model and commandHistory are stored as protected fields innthe Command base class, many commands forget to handle themnappropriately. For example, all commands don't consider the modelnand commandHistory in their `#equals(...)` methods, even thoughnthese fields are part of their state.nn  * Many command tests need to introduce a helper `prepareCommand(...)`nmethod to streamline the command setData and execute process.nnSo, let's fix this by combining Command#setData(...) andnCommand#execute() together. We can then simplify all the command testsnby removing their `prepareCommand(...)` helper methods.n

Combine Command#setData(...) and Command#execute()rntogether to fix this, and allow us to streamline our command testingrncode by removing all of the `prepareCommand(...)` helper methods.rnrn  [1/5] SelectCommandTest: verify model state as wellrn  [2/5] FindCommandTest: verify entire model statern  [3/5] HelpCommandTest: verify model state as wellrn  [4/5] Command tests: verify CommandHistory as wellrn  [5/5] Command: combine setData(...) and execute() together

XmlSerializableAddressBook: check for duplicate person(s)When the address book XML file happens to contain duplicate person(s),nXmlSerializableAddressBook#toModelType() will throw an uncheckednDuplicatePersonException instead of the checked IllegalValueExceptionnwhich it promises to throw.nnThis is because XmlSerializableAddressBook#toModelType() relied onnAddressBook#addPerson(Person) throwing DuplicatePersonException when anduplicate person is encountered. Since DuplicatePersonExceptionninherited from DuplicateDataException, which in turn inherited fromnIllegalValueException, this gave rise to the expected behavior.nnHowever, 6817bd35 (model: make DuplicatePersonException anRuntimeException, 2018-08-07) made DuplicatePersonException inherit fromnRuntimeException. Since this commit, all callers ofnAddressBook#addPerson(Person) are expected to perform the duplicatenperson check using AddressBook#hasPerson(Person). Yet,nXmlSerializableAddressBook#toModelType() was not updated.nnFix this by teaching XmlSerializableAddressBook#toModelType() tonexplicitly check for duplicate persons usingnAddressBook#hasPerson(Person). Add a test to prevent future regressions.n

ModelManager: remove synchronization from methodsSynchronized methods are only useful when multiple threads could accessnthe same object at the same time[1].nnHowever, when our application is run, only the JavaFX application threadnshould have access to the model. When running GUI tests, the main threadn(running the tests) and the JavaFX application thread will both havenaccess to the model, but the synchronization implemented internally innTestFX should ensure that only one thread accesses the model at anyngiven time.nnAs such, the model does not require synchronization. If any of the abovenconditions do not hold, it is a bug and should be fixed directly, notnpapered over by adding locks. Depending on the JVM's implementationndetails and whether is having a good or bad day, such careless use ofnsynchronization could lead to a performance penalty[2].nnSo, let's remove the synchronization from ModelManager's methods, andnremove the synchronization requirement from its javadoc.nn[1]: But even then, they're not a silver bullet.n[2]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/8524882n

storage: implement JsonAddressBookStorage and related classesWe are going to be migrating our storage layer from JAXB (XML) tonJackson (JSON).nnAs a first step, introduce JsonAddressBookStorage and its relatednclasses. These classes implement serializing and deserializingnAddressBooks into JSON format, using Jackson.nnJsonAdaptedPerson, JsonAdaptedTag and JsonSerializableAddressBook sharenmost of the same code and design as their JAXB-based counterpartsn(XmlAdaptedPerson, XmlAdaptedTag and XmlSerializableAddressBook).nnLikewise, copy over the tests from XmlAdaptedPerson, XmlAdaptedTag,nXmlSerializableAddressBook etc. However, unlike XML files, JSON files donnot support comments, and so we'll need to be a bit creative with thentest JSON files.n

Use JSON as the address book serialization formatJAXB has been deprecated and has already been removed in JDK11[1].nnIn response to this, we have been moving towards removing any use ofnJAXB on our codebase. In previous commits, we have implemented anfully-functioning JsonAddressBookStorage, using Jackson, fornserializing/deserializing AddressBooks in JSON format.nnNow, let's flip the switch and make JsonAddressBookStorage _the_nAddressBookStorage that MainApp uses. This means that JSON is now ournofficial address book serialization format.nnA variety of small tweaks need to be made in the same commit to avoidnbreakage:nn  * Since the application stores the address book in JSON format, itnwould be more suitable for all address book-related files to have an`.json` extension instead of an `.xml` extension.nn  * Changing the storage implementation now requires editingnJsonAddressBookStorage, JsonAdaptedPerson etc. instead of the XMLncounterparts. Update the DeveloperGuide to reflect this.nn  * StorageManagerTest contains some integration tests to ensure thatnStorageManager is properly wired to XmlAddressBookStorage. SincenStorageManager now uses JsonAddressBookStorage, modifynStorageManagerTest to reflect that.nn  * Since JsonAddressBookStorage, JsonAdaptedPerson etc. are now thenstorage classes that are actually used, update the storage componentnclass diagram in the DeveloperGuide to reflect this.nn[1] https://openjdk.java.net/jeps/320n

Remove all JAXB/XML-related code from the codebaseJAXB has been deprecated and has already been removed in JDK 11[1].nnOur codebase also does not require JAXB or XML support any more -- wenhave already migrated our codebase to use Jackson (JSON) fully for thenstorage layer.nnSo, let's fully remove all JAXB/XML-related code from the codebase, sonwe can remove JAXB as a dependency from our build.gradle file.nnOnce that is done, we won't have the IntelliJ reports code errors fornJAXB imports problem as described in 5383298a (DeveloperGuide: updatenSetting up section, 2018-09-08). The problem still remains for JavaFX,nhowever. Tweak the DeveloperGuide to reflect this.nn[1] https://openjdk.java.net/jeps/320n

ModelClassBetterOopDiagram: simplify to its bare essentialsModelClassBetterOopDiagram is used in the Developer Guide to show hownthe storage of tags in the model can be tweaked to be made more OOP.nnAs such, ModelClassBetterOopDiagram is mostly similar tonModelClassDiagram with relatively few differences. GuiSettings: make deeply immutableGuiSettings' users (most prominently, UserPrefs), assumes thatnGuiSettings is deeply immutable. UserPrefs: remove setGuiSettings(double, double, int, int)This convenience setter is meant to allow users to set the GuiSettingsnwithout needing to type out `new GuiSettings`.nnHowever,nn  * the convenience this brings is extremely minimal,nn  * we don't usually do convenience setters in the codebase,nn  * setting a precedent of allowing convenience setters in the codebasenwill increase the maintenance burden: if we had x setters that takena class Y, and the class Y has z convenience constructors, we wouldnthen need to have x * z setters in total. Much better to keep thingsnDRY and make developers use the z convenience constructors directly.nnSo, let's remove the convenience setter.n

UserPrefs: make guiSettings non-nullableUserPrefs#guiSettings can be internally `null`. If that is so,nUserPrefs#getGuiSettings() will return a `new GuiSettings()`.nnGenerally, for the AB-4 codebase, we try not to make fields nullablenunless absolutely necessary -- this is because more code will need to benwritten to handle the case when a field is null, and more code = morenbugs.nnIn this case, it is not necessary for guiSettings to be nullable.nIn fact, in normal operation of AB-4, guiSettings will *never* be null:nn  * When deserializing a JSON file which does not have guiSettingsnspecified, the default value of guiSettings will be used, which isnnot null. (This is because deserialization will call the no-argnconstructor of UserPrefs, which will initialize guiSettings to annon-null value)nn  * For all usages of UserPrefs#setGuiSettings(...), the providednGuiSettings is not null.nnSo, let's make this field non-nullable.nn(In fact, if guiSettings is null, UserPrefs#toString() will throw an NPEn:-P)n

UserPrefs: enforce addressBookFilePath non-nullable invariantOur codebase assumes that UserPrefs#addressBookFilePath is non-nullablen-- all usages of UserPrefs#getAddressBookFilePath() don't handle thencase when addressBookFilePath is null.nnHowever, UserPrefs does not enforce this invariant. BrowserPanel: remove freeResources()It claims to free resources allocated to the browser by doing:nnbrowser = null;nnbut it's unclear why that must be done. (In fact, most GCs do notnguarantee freeing a resource immediately once it becomes garbage.)nnAlso of note is that the HelpWindow, which also uses a browser, does notnhave this freeResources() workaround. Since we haven't gotten anynreports of problems with the HelpWindow browser, it is likely that thisnfreeResources() workaround is not needed.nnSo, let's just remove it.n

ci: do not retry on test failuresWhenever test failures occur, our Travis and Appveyor configurationsnwill re-run the entire test script, up to 3 times.nnRe-running tests is usually used as a workaround when certain tests arenflaky. However, in this case, it does more harm than good:nn  * If the tests are indeed failing due to a problem with the code, thenbuild time would still be extremely long due to the unnecessaryntest-retrying. This could cause unnecessary jams in our buildnqueues.nn  * If we accidentally introduce a flaky test, developers who only testnvia the CI, and do not view the logs of CI jobs that pass, willnlikely not find out since the tests are re-run until they passn(unless they happen to fail all 3 times).  For development purposes,nit is more beneficial if we are alerted to flaky tests as soon asnpossible, preferably before the code is even merged.nn  * If we _do_ have flaky tests, the tests should be individually markednto be retried using JUnit's mechanisms, rather than leaving it tonthe CI configuration. This would both help save build time (sincenonly the flaky test would be re-run) and would be more explicitn(since the flaky test is clearly marked out in code).nnAs such, let's change our CI configuration to not retry on testnfailures.n

We only neednone single DummySearchPage to be published at one single public URL, andnthus these build steps are unnecessary for downstream forks.nnWe have already copied the DummySearchPage and published it atnhttps://se-edu.github.io/dummy-search-page/. Logic: expose command history as an ObservableListThe command history is exposed to the UI via Logic#getHistorySnapshot(),nwhich returns a ListElementPointer.nnHowever, this API interface is unnecessarily limiting by assuming thatnclients would only want to look at the history by iterating through itsncontents one-by-one. It makes it difficult for the UI to expose thencommand history to the user via other means, such as showing the fullnhistory in a ListBox.nnFix this by exposing the command history as an ObservableList, whichnsupports a much wider range of operations. Making it observable wouldnalso make it more consistent with the observable design of ournModel/Logic APIs to make it easy for UI elements to respond to changesnin model data.nnSince ListElementPointer is not used by the logic layer anymore, move itnto the seedu.address.ui package. This is likely a much more suitablenpackage for it, as its design is pretty specialized to how CommandBoxnoperates and thus it likely can't find much use elsewhere.n

MainWindowCloseTest: remove unnecessary stage.setScene(...)Since MainWindow initializes itself directly into the provided `stage`,nthe `stage`'s scene is _already_ the `mainWindow`'s scene, so thisncall is redundant. Remove it.n

MainApp: don't forcefully terminate the application on exitWhen MainApp receives an ExitAppRequestEvent, it forcefully terminatesnthe application with:nnPlatform.exit();nSystem.exit(0);nnHowever, this makes testing the `exit` command extremely hard. This isnbecause in the JUnit environment, calling System.exit(...) will causenthe test runner to terminate as well, causing tests to not properly benrun. Likewise, TestFX expects the JavaFX event loop to be running fornthe entire duration of all tests, and thus calling Platform.exit() willncause TestFX to become stuck [1]. As such, tests such asnMainWindowCloseTest work around this by checking to see if thenExitAppRequestEvent is raised instead.nnBut really, we don't need to call Platform.exit() or System.exit().nThis is because by default, once all windows are closed, JavaFX willnautomatically begin the shutdown process and call Application#stop().nnAs such, let's tweak our implementation so that we trigger JavaFXnshutdown by closing all windows -- namely, closing all MainWindows andnHelpWindows.nnThis is accomplished by shifting the handling of ExitAppRequestEvent tonMainWindow. MainWindow will handle it by hiding itself and itsnHelpWindow. Since there can only be one HelpWindow to each MainWindow,nand all MainWindows will respond to the ExitAppRequestEvent, this wouldnessentially cause all open windows to be hidden.nnLikewise, MainWindowCloseTest does not need to check fornExitAppRequestEvent any more -- it can simply check if all windows arenclosed (and the JavaFX framework shutdown is thus implied). This wouldnmake it more like a black box test and thus more resilient to changes inninternal implementation details in the future.nn[1] See 088db25e (MainWindow.fxml: update onCloseRequest event to callnhandleExit(), 2018-02-16) for a discussion of these issues.n

BrowserPanel#DEFAULT_PAGE: provide full URLBrowserPanel#DEFAULT_PAGE has the value of default.html. However, thenvalue itself doesn't give us the full picture since it does not tell usn_where_ exactly default.html is located.nnAs such, our test code has to duplicate this information in variousnplaces:nnMainApp.class.getResource(FXML_FILE_FOLDER + DEFAULT_PAGE)nn(namely, that default.html is inside the FXML_FILE_FOLDER, andnFXML_FILE_FOLDER is relative to MainApp's package)nnRemove this duplication of information by making DEFAULT_PAGE providenthe _full_ URL, so that we can DRY up the test code.nnAt the same time, wrap the initialization of DEFAULT_PAGE with anrequireNonNull(...), so that we can detect as early as possible whethernthe default.html page is missing, which should help in debugging.n

Keep a strong reference to created unmodifiableObservableListsThe observable list created withnFXCollections.unmodifiableObservableList(...) installs a weak listenern-- that is, the backing list only keeps a weak reference to thenunmodifiable list. This means that if there is no other strong referencenpointing to the created unmodifiable observable list, it would bengarbage collected.nnThis becomes a problem when other code attaches event listeners to thenunmodifiable list, with the expectation that it would be called whenevernthe backing list changes. When the unmodifiable list is garbagencollected, the event listeners will not be called any more, which couldncause incorrect application behavior.nnFix this by making the code base keep a strong reference to eachnunmodifiable observable list, and return the same unmodifiablenobservable list whenever its getter is called.n

ui: move command execution responsibility from CommandBox to MainWindowCommandBox is the UiPart responsible for command execution (i.e callingnLogic#execute(String) and processing its return value).nnIn the next few commits, we want the methods of other UiParts to bencalled when command execution occurs.nnHowever, CommandBox does not have access to the other UiParts in thenmain window. (And it should not, to be consistent with our architecturendesign).nnOn the other hand, MainWindow _does_ have access to the other UiParts innthe MainWindow.nnAs such, let's make MainWindow responsible for command execution.nCommandBox will use callbacks to notify MainWindow that it shouldnexecute a command.nnSince now MainWindow, instead of CommandBox, is the class that directlyncalls Logic#execute(String), update the Ui class diagram to reflect thisnupdated relationship.n

ResultDisplay: migrate away from EventsCenterWhen MainWindow gets a CommandResult or exception from callingnLogic#execute(String), it would notify ResultDisplay of the result bynposting a NewResultAvailableEvent to EventsCenter.nnAs we are going to remove EventsCenter in the future, let's migratenResultDisplay away from EventCenter.nnRather than having this event-posting-and-receiving arrangement, let'snadd a ResultDisplay#setFeedbackToUser() method to ResultDisplay, andnteach MainWindow to call this method when it receives a CommandResultnfrom Logic#execute(String).n

HelpCommand: use CommandResult to signal MainWindow to show helpTo show the help window, HelpCommand will post a ShowHelpRequestEvent tonEventsCenter. MainWindow will then respond to it by showing thenHelpWindow.nnAs we are going to remove EventsCenter in the future, let's migrate thisnmechanism away from EventsCenter.nnLet's add a `showHelp` flag to CommandResult, and teach HelpCommand tonuse this flag to signal to MainWindow to show the HelpWindow. TeachnMainWindow to respond to this flag by showing the HelpWindow.nnSince most commands would _not_ be setting the `showHelp` flag, let'snalso add a CommandResult(String) convenience constructor, that just setsnthe `feedbackToUser`.nnAs CommandResult now contains more than one field, rather than justnverifying `feedbackToUser`, our tests would need to verify the entirenstate of the CommandResult object to be thorough. As such, let's teachnCommandTestUtil#assertCommandSuccess(...) to verify the entirenCommandResult object. At the same time, as mentioned above, mostncommands would not be setting any of the flags in CommandResult. Asnsuch, let's add a convenience wrapper that accepts a stringn`feedbackToUser`.nnUpdate the Developer Guide to show that CommandResult can now instructnthe Ui to perform certain actions, such as displaying help to the user.n

ExitCommand: use CommandResult to signal MainWindow to exitTo make the application exit, ExitCommand will post anExitAppRequestEvent to EventsCenter. MainWindow will then respond bynhiding itself (and its HelpWindow if open). Since JavaFX will exit whennall windows are closed, this will cause the application to exit.nnAs we are going to remove EventsCenter in the future, let's migrate thisnmechanism away from EventsCenter.nnLet's add an `exit` flag to CommandResult, and teach ExitCommand to usenthis flag to signal to MainWindow to exit. Teach MainWindow to respondnto this flag by hiding itself (and its HelpWindow if open).n

BrowserPanel/PersonListPanel: migrate away from EventsCenterThe selection of a person in the filtered person list is communicated tonPersonListPanel and BrowserPanel via events through EventsCenter:nn  * SelectCommand will first post a JumpToListRequestEvent tonEventsCenter. PersonListPanel will then respond by scrolling to thatnperson in the list and selecting it.nn  * When the PersonListPanel's selection changes (via the abovenmechanism or when the user selects a new person via the list panel),nPersonListPanel will post a PersonPanelSelectionChangedEvent tonEventsCenter. BrowserPanel will then respond by navigating to thenperson's respective URL.nnAs we are going to remove EventsCenter in the future, let's migratenthese mechanisms away from EventsCenter:nn  * We first explicitly model the currently selected person in Model.nSelectCommand would thus select a person by callingnModel#setSelectedPerson(Person).nn  * Next, we teach PersonListPanel and BrowserPanel to listen fornchanges to the selected person by observingnModel#selectedPersonProperty().nn  * Finally, we teach PersonListPanel to callnModel#setSelectedPerson(Person) if the user changes the selectednperson via the UI.nnThis approach is chosen over alternatives (such as re-implementing thenoriginal event-based approach directly using callbacks) as it providesnthe following additional advantages:nn  * Since, by our definition, the selected person must _always_ be anvalid person in the filtered person list, it naturally implements anuser request[1] to clear the browser panel when the address book isncleared.nn  * It provides a single source of truth for the currently selectednperson, and thus opening up the possibility of us implementingncommands in the future that operate on the currently selectednperson, rather than requring users to provide an index each time.nn[1] https://github.com/se-edu/addressbook-level4/issues/731n

AddressBook: make ObservableIn the next few commits, we will be removing AddressBookChangedEvent innorder to migrate the codebase away from EventsCenter.nnHowever, to do so, the codebase needs another way to monitor AddressBooknfor changes.nnThey could do so by listening for changes to AddressBook's person listn(which is an ObservableList). This might work since any changes to annAddressBook is done to its person list. However, its not a future-proofnsolution as we may add more fields to AddressBook in the future, whichnwould need to be observed as well.nnAs such, let's implement a more comprehensive solution by makingnAddressBook implement the Observable interface, so that our codebase cannmonitor AddressBook for changes by attaching invalidation listeners tonit. Whenever a mutating method of AddressBook is called, the attachedninvalidation listeners will be called. This design can be consistentlynused no matter how many pieces of data AddressBook stores.nnThe javafx.beans.Observable interface was chosen to allow thisnimplementation to interoperate easily with JavaFX's API.nnCo-authored-by: Zhi Yuan Yong <yongzhiyuan@u.nus.edu>n

StatusBarFooter: migrate away from EventsCenterStatusBarFooter has a last updated status which displays when thenaddress book was last modified.nnThis is implemented as follows: When ModelManager's address book isnmodified, it will post an AddressBookChangedEvent event to EventsCenter.nStatusBarFooter will then respond to it by updating its last updatednstatus to the current time.nnAs we are going to remove EventsCenter in the future, let's migrate thisnmechanism away from EventsCenter.nnRather than listening for AddressBookChangedEvents, lets teachnStatusBarFooter to listen for invalidation events from the AddressBookndirectly.n

Address book storage: migrate away from EventsCenterWhen the model's address book is modified, ModelManager will post annAddressBookChangedEvent to EventsCenter. StorageManager will thennrespond by calling StorageManager#saveAddressBook(...) to save thenaddress book.nnIf an error occurs while saving the address book, StorageManager willnpost a DataSavingExceptionEvent to EventsCenter. UiManager will thennrespond by showing an alert dialog.nnAs we are going to remove EventsCenter in the future, let's migratenthese mechanisms away from EventsCenter.nnLet's teach LogicManager to listen for invalidation events fromnModelManager's AddressBook. If an invalidation event occurs (whichnindicates that the AddressBook was likely modified), LogicManager willnthen call Storage#saveAddressBook(...) after command execution. If annerror occurs, this will then be sent to the caller via exceptions. Thenend result is that the control flow is much clearer and explicit in thencode.nnNote that the new implementation differs in the handling of address booknstorage errors: previously an error dialog would be shown. Now, thenerror would be reported by the ResultDisplay. This approach is chosen asnits much simpler -- we can simply reuse the same battle-tested codenpaths for handling command errors. Furthermore, the overall goal isnstill achieved as the error is still reported to the user.nnThe Developer Guide describes in detail how address book saving worksnunder the section Events-Driven nature of the design. As such, we'llnneed to update it. Since at this point most of the codebase is not usingnEventsCenter, let's rewrite the entire section into one that describes,nin high-level detail, how architectural components interact with eachnother.n

Remove EventsCenterThe codebase isn't using EventsCenter anymore, so let's remove it.nnUpdate the Developer Guide and Learning Outcomes document to remove anynmention of EventsCenter, as well as any mention of EventsCenter events.nnNote that the Suggested Programming Tasks to get Started section innthe Developer Guide is left untouched in this commit and should benupdated in the future.n

PersonCard: display tags in sorted orderThe code in PersonCard for displaying Tags as Labels is as follows:nnperson.getTags().forEach(tag -> tags.getChildren().add(new Label(tag.tagName)));nnHowever, `person.getTags()` is a Set (stored internally as a HashSet).nSets do not provide any ordering guarantees, which means that the ordernin which tags are displayed in the PersonCard is potentiallynnon-deterministic. This means that two people having the same tags couldnpotentially have their tags displayed in different orders, which couldnconfuse and annoy users who expect AddressBook to behave in anpredictable manner.nnFix this by sorting the tags first before adding them as Labels, thusnimposing an ordering on the tags. Lexicographical ordering based on thentag name is used since that's a commonly used ordering criterion.n

StringUtilTest: Remove Hamcrest String matcherCurrently, in StringUtilTest#getDetails_exceptionGiven, we usenHamcrest's string matching and assert libraries.nThis library was introduced in [1], however no justification wasngiven on why we specifically used these Hamcrest libraries. DeveloperGuide: update Troubleshooting Testing sectionDue to new privacy enhancements introduced in macOS Mojave, applicationsnwithout `Accessibility` permission cannot simulate keyboard and mousenmovements.nnThis causes GUI tests that uses `CommandBoxHandle#run(...)` to executencommands to fail, as `CommandBoxHandle#run(...)` attempts to simulatenpressing `Enter` key in the Command Box using `GuiRobot` (subclass ofn`org.testfx.api.FxRobot`).nnThe `Enter` keypress event is then handled byn`CommandBox#handleCommandEntered()`, which executes the command.nnHowever, because of insufficient privileges, `GuiRobot` may be unable tonsimulate the `Enter` keypress event in the Command Box, thus the handlernmethod is not called. This results in the command in the Command Box tonnot get executed, which in turn causes the GUI tests to fail.nnTo reduce confusion amongst developers using macOS Mojave, let's updatenthe Troubleshooting Testing section to discuss this issue, and provideninstructions on how to resolve it.n

TestApp: Move SAVE_LOCATION_FOR_TESTING into AddressBookSystemTestTestApp has a constant SAVE_LOCATION_FOR_TESTING.nSAVE_LOCATION_FOR_TESTING is used only withinnAddressBookSystemTest#getDataFileLocation. In fact,nAddressBookSystemTest retrieves the value ofnSAVE_LOCATION_FOR_TESTING, then passes it intonSetupHelper#setupApplication, which then invokes TestApp to initialisenthe saveFileLocation parameter. AddressBookSystemTest essentiallynviolates the tell-don't-ask principle, as it retrieves the constantnand later makes TestApp set that value. Since AddressBookSystemTest isnresponsible for initialising TestApp with these constants (in fact itnis the only class using these constants), moving the constants tonAddressBookSystemTest increases cohesion within the class.nnThis design has been in AB4 since its draft stage [1], and while nonreason was given, it is likely that this implementation was adopted sonas to allow other classes (such as SampleDataTest) to initialisenTestApp with different saveFileLocations.nnLet's move SAVE_LOCATION_FOR_TESTING to AddressBookSystemTest.nn[1] https://github.com/se-edu/addressbook-level4/blame/ed799215c859845f1d33131d1089fcb2727c38a6/src/test/java/seedu/address/TestApp.javan

TestApp: Move DEFAULT_PREF_LOCATION_FOR_TESTING into AddressBookSystemTestThe location for the preference file is fixed within TestApp as anconstant. TestApp#initConfig overrides MainApp#initConfig, so when thenTestApp starts, the preferences file is always initialised to a fixednfile. This reduces the flexibility for testing.nnIn contrast, the saveFileLocation is a variable that is set by classesnthat initialise TestApp, such as AddressBookSystemTest. ThensaveFileLocation can be easily mocked and tested, as compared to thenfixed prefFileLocation. Even though we currently have no tests thatnuse a custom prefFileLocation, having one increases our flexibilitynin testing as we can simply write classes similar to (or extending)nAddressBookSystemTest to supply a custom prefFileLocation.nnLet's move DEFAULT_PREF_LOCATION_FOR_TESTING intonAddressBookSystemTest.nnAs a result, the name of the constant changes - it is no longer andefault preference location. This brings the variable name in linenwith SAVE_LOCATION_FOR_TESTING.nFurthermore, TestApp now needs to be initialised with the value ofnprefFileLocation. Standardize Assert#assertThrows(...) calls to use static importWe use a mixture of calling the staticnAssert.assertThrows(...) and calling a statically importednAssert#assertThrows.nnThis can make it confusing for readers, as we have 2 different ways ofncalling the same assertThrows.nnLet's standardise, across all tests, to use a statically importednAssert#assertThrows. This also has the benefit of making our code lessnverbose and easier to read.n

LogicManagerTest: Split assertCommandBehavior into assertCommandSuccess and assertCommandFailureWhen given an exception, assertCommandBehavior ensures that thencorrect exception is thrown. When given null, assertCommandBehaviornensures that no exception is thrown. While the function cleverlynavoids the use of if/else statements, it is difficult for a reader tonunderstand the flow of assertCommandBehavior. It is also responsiblenfor two distinct tasks and violates the single responsibilitynprinciple. Additionally, assertCommandBehavior is not descriptive -nwhat behaviour are we assuring ourselves?nnWhen assertCommandBehavior was first introduced, no documentation wasnmade on the design choice. It is likely that this was implementednbecause JUnit did not provide an API to check for thrown exceptions.nWith a single method able to check for both exceptions and its lacknthereof, it made sense to implement assertCommandBehavior to reducencode repetition.nnNow, with Assert#assertThrows, the call to checking for thrownnexceptions is just one line. The cost in difficulty in understandingnhow assertCommandBehavior works and its violation of SinglenResponsibility Principle now outweighs the benefits of the reducedncode repetition.nnLet's separate assertCommandBehavior into assertCommandSuccess andnassertCommandFailure instead, to make our code easier to understandnand more in line with the Single Responsibility Principle.n

Thrown exception checking: Migrate to use AssertThrowsWe use a mix of 4 different ways to test exception throwing. We use:n* try/catch - catch and ensure we receive the correct exception.n* Assert#assertThrowsn* JUnit#assertThrowsn* JUnit#ExpectedException.nAll these methods semantically do the same thing.nnTo streamline and standardise our code, we should only use one way toncheck for thrown exceptions. Rationale: developers only need to learnnone style of implementation.nnThe try/catch method is implemented differently in each file thatnrequires it and causes unnecessary code duplication. The assertThrowsnstyle, in comparison, provides a shorter syntax and is easier to readnas compared to the ExpectedException style or the try/catch style.nWe should thus aim to use the assertThrows style.nnIn Assert.java, we implement custom methods that provide additionalnfunctionality such as testing for correctness of error messages shownnto users. With Assert#assertThrows providing a superset ofnfunctionality as compared to all other ways, it makes sense to usenAssert#assertThrows as the standardised way to test for thrownnexceptions.nnLet's convert all our exception checking to use Assert#assertThrows.nnIn doing so, some tests no longer need to declare to throw exceptions.nnLet's clean up our code to remove these unnecessary declarations.nnAdditionally, two more classes - StringUtilTest and IndexTest -nimplement methods to encapsulate the idea of checking for thrownnexceptions. Now that we can directly call Assert#assertThrows, thesenabstractions provide little benefit.nnLet's remove them to simplify our code base.n

Tests: standardize the way we check for thrown exceptions (#1007)We have many different ways of checking for thrown exceptions. These arernnot standardized, and make it difficult for a reader because they havernto learn the different ways of throwing exceptions.rnrnLet's standardize the way we test exception throwing behavior,rnspecifically towards using Assert#assertThrows.rnrn  [1/3] Standardize Assert#assertThrows(...) calls to use static importrn  [2/3] LogicManagerTest: Split assertCommandBehavior into assertCommandSuccess and assertCommandFailurern  [3/3] Thrown exception checking: Migrate to use AssertThrows

build.gradle: Remove TestFX-JUnit dependencyWe include the TestFX-JUnit dependency in our build.gradle since [1].rnHowever, we also implement our own StageRule and SystemTestSetupHelperrnto setup the UI environment for unit tests and system testsrnrespectively. These classes replicate TestFX-JUnit's ApplicationTestrnbehavior [2], so our tests do not need to extend from ApplicationTest.rnrnAccording to TestFX's documentation [3], TestFX-JUnit provides thernApplicationTest class that we can inherit from. Since we alreadyrnimplement the necessary setup routine, we do not need to inherit fromrnApplicationTest. TestFX-JUnit thus adds no value to our project now.rnrnLet's remove the TestFX-JUnit dependency.rnrn[1]: https://github.com/se-edu/addressbook-level4/commit/7916322fad9d11ef3fa7ca67574062bb6de3e950rn[2]: https://github.com/TestFX/TestFX/blob/master/subprojects/testfx-junit/src/main/java/org/testfx/framework/junit/ApplicationTest.javarn[3]: https://github.com/TestFX/TestFX/blob/master/README.md#assertj-based-assertions

CheckStyle: Allow exceptions for JUnit 5 test annotationsWe use CheckStyle to check and uphold some of our coding standards.nWhile CheckStyle works properly for majority of our code, some testnAPIs work differently. For example, it is necessary to declare publicnvariables in the case of:n@Rulenpublic TemporaryFolder testFolder = new TemporaryFolder();nTo suppress CheckStyle warnings for these poor coding practice, wenallow exceptions when we detect certain annotations. For example,nanything immediately succeeding a @Rule tag can be declared as public.nnAs we migrate to JUnit 5, we need to add exceptions for the equivalentntest annotations used in JUnit 5 [1]. For example, BeforeClass is nownBeforeAll. JUnit 5 also introduces new annotations such as the TempDirnand RegisterExtension annotation.nnHence, let'sn* add JUnit 5 annotations such as BeforeAll/BeforeEach tonallowedAnnotations in Javadoc modulen* add TempDir and RegisterExtension annotation tonignoreAnnotationCanonicalNames in VisibilityModifier module.nnKeeping in mind that some tests are still written in JUnit 4 stylenduring this transition phase, when adding the TempDir andnRegisterExtension annotations, we cannot remove exceptions fornexisting annotations (such as Rule and ClassRule). Hence, in thenVisibilityModifier module, when we override the default value to addnTempDir and RegisterExtension, we also need to add Rule and ClassRulentags which are in use by existing code [2].nn[1] As of March 2019,nhttp://checkstyle.sourceforge.net/config_javadoc.html#JavadocMethodndoes not have JUnit 5 annotations.n[2] Default modifiers are Rule, ClassRule and VisibleForTesting.nhttp://checkstyle.sourceforge.net/config_design.html#VisibilityModifiern

Assert: Use JUnit 5 Assert#assertThrowsAssert contains a custom assertThrows method.nnThis implementation was done when we used JUnit 4 which has no propernsupport for assertThrows. This is now unnecessary as JUnit 5'snAssertions.assertThrows performs the same functionality.nnLet's replace Assert#assertThrows with JUnit 5's assertThrows.nnWith this change, VoidCallable becomes redundant as its behaviournis replicated with JUnit 5's Executable interface.nnLet's remove it.nn[1] https://github.com/junit-team/junit5/blob/5e41ebe612fd67e905f96f1dd3184a071b65be17/junit-jupiter-api/src/main/java/org/junit/jupiter/api/function/Executable.javan

JUnit Assert: Migrate to JUnit 5 APIWe use JUnit 4's Assert API. For example, in most classes, we importnorg.junit.Assert.assertFalse or org.junit.Assert.assertEquals.nnIn JUnit 5, the API has migrated tonorg.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.*. While the functionality remainsnlargely similar, JUnit 4 APIs are no longer supported by the JUnit 5nrunner (unless a legacy Vintage engine is used [1]). Thus, it isnnecessary to use JUnit 5 APIs as we migrate our tests to JUnit 5.nnLet's migrate our API calls to assertion statements to use thenones provided by JUnit 5 instead.nThis can be done by changing all references of org.junit.Assert.* tonorg.junit.jupiter.Assertions.*.nnIn this migration, some methods signatures such as assertTrue(String,nBoolean) has been changed to assertTrue(Boolean, String). The relevantnmethod calls have been updated to reflect this signature change.nn[1]: https://junit.org/junit5/docs/current/user-guide/#migrating-from-junit4n

JUnit: Upgrade to JUnit 5.4.0We write our tests using the JUnit 5.1.0 API. The JUnit 5.1.0 APIncontains most features we require, such as assertTrue or assertThrows.nnWe have unit tests such as StorageManagerTest#prefsReadSave thatnrequire writing to the filesystem. These tests need to make use ofntemporary directories. This is so thatn(1) we can begin with a clean, known state at the start of each testnandn(2) we can prevent our test output from polluting the user's filensystem.nnHowever, JUnit 5.1.0 does not support creating temporary directoriesnnatively, so developers need to create a custom TemporaryDirectorynimplementation or rely on JUnit-Pioneer library [1]. Both of thesensolutions make it complicated to implement and for future developersnto understand.nnJUnit 5.4.0 is the first version of JUnit that has a native temporaryndirectory API [2]. By upgrading to JUnit 5.4.0, we can directly usenthe org.junit.jupiter.api.io.TempDir API.nThis reduces the complexity of implementing a temporary directory.nnLet's upgrade to use JUnit 5.4.0.nn[1] https://medium.com/@GalletVictor/migration-from-junit-4-to-junit-5-d8fe38644aben[2] https://github.com/junit-team/junit5/issues/1247n

JUnit: Migrate to use JUnit 5 test runnerWe use JUnit 4 test runner (org.junit.Test) to execute our unit andnsystem testing.nnTo use new features such as callbacks, extensions and temporaryndirectories in JUnit 5, we need to use the new JUnit 5 test runner.nnLet'sn* use the new org.junit.jupiter.api.Test instead of org.junit.Testn* use BeforeEach instead of Beforen* use BeforeAll instead of BeforeClassn* use AfterEach instead of Aftern* use AfterAll instead of AfterClassnnNote: Tests that involve TemporaryFolders, JavaFX, UiPartRule,nStageRule and ClockRule will be migrated in another commit, so asnto limit the scope of each commit.n

TemporaryFolder: Migrate to JUnit 5 TempDir APIWe use JUnit 4's TemporaryFolder rule to initialise a temporarynfolder.nnRules are no longer supported by JUnit 5 test runners. In addition,nJUnit 5.4.0 introduces the TempDir extension that supersedes thenTemporaryFolder rule.nnLet's migrate our usage of TemporaryFolder rules to TempDir.nnAs TempDirs in JUnit 5 are Paths, it is no longer necessary to invokenmethods like getRoot().toPath() on the TempDir. Additionally, the waynto get a URL resource from the TempDir is also different fromnTemporaryFolder. The relevant methods have been updated.nnIn LogicManagerTest and MainWindowCloseTest, the newFile() API is notnsupported by JUnit 5's TempDir. However, as the random file namenprovided by newFile() is not necessary (we have full control over thencontents of the temporary directory), instead of re-implementingnnewFile() to match the behavior of existing tests, we explicitly giventhe file names and use Path.resolve() instead.n

UiTest: Migrate StageRule to StageExtension and UiPartRule to UiPartExtensionWe use JUnit 4 style tests in the UI segment of unit tests.nJUnit 5 offers a more declarative and extension-based unit test, tonencourage reuse of components common to all tests.nnAs we migrate towards JUnit 5, it is essential that we migrate the UInunit tests to adopt JUnit 5's style. Most importantly, JUnit 5nreplaces Rules with Extensions, hence we need to migrate UiPartRule tonUiPartExtension and StageRule to StageExtension.nnLet's replace UiPartRule with UiPartExtension, and StageRule withnStageExtension, taking advantage of JUnit 5's extensive hook interfacen(BeforeEachCallback and AfterEachCallback) to simplify ournimplementation of hooks. Notably, we no longer need to implement ournown before/hook/after sequence.nnHowever, this migration introduces a complication. As extensions arenspecific to JUnit 5, we cannot use extensions without switching thentest runner to JUnit 5's Jupiter test runner. However, this switchnmeans that we also need to migrate other API changes.nNotably,n* Before/BeforeClass becomes BeforeEach/BeforeAlln* After/AfterClass becomes AfterEach/AfterAllnnFurthermore, HelpWindowTest needs to continue skipping the test innheadless mode, due to a bug (still yet to be fixed) in JavaFX. Thenequivalent API in JUnit 5 is located innorg.junit.jupiter.api.Assumptions.*, so in order to continue skippingnthe test, we need to migrate the call and update its method signaturenas necessary.n

ClockRule: Migrate to ClockExtensionWe use ClockRule to implement a clock for unit testing.nnRules are part of JUnit 4, and have been replaced by extensions innJUnit 5. As we migrate to JUnit 5, we should update ClockRule tonfollow the new naming convenion and use JUnit 5 extension style.nnLet's rewrite ClockRule to implement an injectable clock using JUnit5ncallbacks.nnWith a ClockExtension now migrated to JUnit 5 API, we need to updatenAddressBookSystemTest to use the JUnit 5 runner too, so that thenClockExtension can be activated. As a result, all system tests thatnextend from AddressBookSystemTest also need to be updated to use thenJUnit 5 runner.nMigration to the JUnit 5 runner means that we also need to updatenother API changes such as:n* Before/BeforeClass becomes BeforeEach/BeforeAlln* After/AfterClass becomes AfterEach/AfterAlln* Rules are no longer supported, extensions are registed withnRegisterExtension instead.n

Checkstyle: Remove exceptions for JUnit 4 annotationsCheckstyle contains exceptions to allow certain exceptions in codingnstyle for JUnit 4 tests. For example, Checkstyle allows declaration ofna public variable if it is preceded by a Rule tag so as to ensurencorrect variable assignment by JUnit 4.nnAfter migrating all tests to JUnit 5, we no longer need thesenexceptions for annotations specific to JUnit 4. Hence, we can removenthese annotations to tighten our strictness on coding style.nnHence, let's remove exceptions in checkstyle for JUnit 4 annotations.nNotably, let's removen* Before/BeforeClass/After/AfterClass tags used to denote functions tonrun before/after a testn* Rule/ClassRule tags used to denote rules (now extensions in JUnit 5)n

Build.gradle: Remove JUnit 4 librariesCurrently, we use a mix of both JUnit 4 and 5 libraries, using JUnitnVintage to maintain compatibility with JUnit 4 tests.nnAfter migrating all tests to JUnit 5, we no longer need thesenlibraries to support JUnit 4. Hence, we can remove these librariesnfrom build.gradle to reduce the number of unncessary components, thusnstreamlining our codebase.nnLet's remove JUnit 4 test and support libraries from build.gradle.n

build.gradle: fix checkstyle plugin failureThe `checkstyle` plugin of Gradle fails in JDK11 and gives the errornbelow:nnUnable to create Root Module: config ...nnThe main reason is that, in JDK11, the `user.dir` cannot be reset bynGradle [1]. So, checkstyle plugin is unable to locate the suppressionsnfile correctly.nnLet's add `config_loc` variable suggested by Gradle to solve thenproblem [1].nn[1] https://github.com/gradle/gradle/issues/8286n

build.gradle: add platform-specific javafx runtime dependenciesJavaFX is not distributed with Oracle JDK any more from JDK11nonwards [1]. Our code uses javafx as our client platform. So it isnunable to be compiled in JDK11 anymore.nnAs we are moving to JDK11, let's add javafx runtime dependencies tongradle.nnMeanwhile, the dependencies provided are platform specific. Let's usenthe SystemUtils api provided by Apache [2] to specify the version ofnjavafx dependencies. A buildscript block is also added to declarenexternal dependencies used for the build script [3].nn[1] https://blogs.oracle.com/java-platform-group/the-future-of-javafx-and-other-java-client-roadmap-updatesn[2] http://commons.apache.org/proper/commons-lang/javadocs/api-release/index.htmln[3] https://docs.gradle.org/current/userguide/tutorial_using_tasks.html#sec:build_script_external_dependenciesn

Change the entry point of addressbookAfter adding the javafx runtime dependency, addressbook is still unablento run in a JDK11 environment. It gives an error of below:nnError: JavaFX runtime components are missing, and are required to run this applicationnnThis error comes from sun.launcher.LauncherHelper in the java.basenmodule. The reason for this is that the MainApp extends Applicationnand has a main method. If that is the case, the LauncherHelper willncheck for the javafx.graphics module to be present as a named module.nIf that module is not present, the launch is aborted. Hence, havingnthe JavaFX libraries as jars on the classpath is not allowed in thisncase [1].nnThis is more like a JDK 11 problem which cannot be solved elegantly.nOne simple workaround is to have a separate main class that doesn'tnextend Application. Hence it doesn't do the check on javafx.graphicsnmodule, and when the required jars are on the classpath, it works fine.nnLet's add another main class to be the new entry point of addressbooknto solve this problem [2].nn[1] http://mail.openjdk.java.net/pipermail/openjfx-dev/2018-June/021977.htmln[2] https://stackoverflow.com/questions/52653836/maven-shade-javafx-runtime-components-are-missing/52654791#52654791n

build.gradle: add javafx runtime dependency for all platformsWe have added the platform-specific javafx runtime dependencies, so thenaddressbook is able to run locally.nnHowever, the jar file generated on one OS cannot run on other OS. Thenreason is that, after detecting the OS, javafx will try to loadnplatform-specific classes dynamically. Without corresponding javafxndependencies for that other OS, the class loading process will fail.nnLet's add the javafx runtime dependency for all platforms (MacOS,nWindow, Linux) so the jar file generated on one OS is able to run innother OS [1].nnFollowing are some key facts that guarantee the solution to work:nn  * Gradle places all dependency JARs on the classpath and the order isnnot defined by Gradle.nn  * When shadowJar encounters duplicate classes with same package namenand same class name, it picks the first one it sees. ShadowJarnprocesses dependency JARs according to their order in classpath.nn  * The platform-specific JARs for different OSs can define the samenclasses. (e.g. javafx-graphics-11-win.jar andnjavafx-graphics-11-linux.jar both containnjavafx/scene/control/TreeView.class). However, via diffing thencontents of the JARs, we have verified that if two JARs define thensame class, the class files are also identical to each other. So, itndoesn't matter if the TreeView.class from javafx-graphics-11-win.jarnor the TreeView.class from javafx-graphics-11-linux.jar is loaded.nAs such, no matter what order Gradle places JavaFX's JARs on thenclasspath, we can run and distribute addressbook properly.nn[1] https://stackoverflow.com/questions/52653836/maven-shade-javafx-runtime-components-are-missing/52654791#52654791n

Workaround headless test failure on Windows OSFor headless test task, 'prism.order' property is used to choose thengraph renderer to use. Currently, we specify this property to be 'sw'.nnHowever, this property triggers a bug of openjdk-jfx with headlessnmode [1]. This property will cause Java Runtime Error for Windows OSnincluding AppVeyor:nn# A fatal error has been detected by the Java Runtime Environment:n#n#  EXCEPTION_ACCESS_VIOLATION (0xc0000005) at pc=0x00007ffd95b64879, pid=1476, tid=2640n#n# JRE version: OpenJDK Runtime Environment (11.0.1+13) (build 11.0.1+13)n# Java VM: OpenJDK 64-Bit Server VM (11.0.1+13, mixed mode, tiered, compressed oops, g1 gc, windows-amd64)n# Problematic frame:n# C  [javafx_font.dll+0x4879]nnThis bug has been identified and will be fixed in future release [2].nThere is a workaround suggested which adds static initializationnblocks to load required library before any FxToolkit code [3].nnJava will initialize base classes first before classes of instancenmembers [4] [5]. For all GUI tests, they uses GuiUnitTest ornAddressBookSystemTest as their base class. Let's add the staticninitialization blocks to these two classes to solve the problem.nn[1] https://github.com/javafxports/openjdk-jfx/issues/66n[2] https://github.com/javafxports/openjdk-jfx/issues/66#issuecomment-472693380n[3] https://github.com/javafxports/openjdk-jfx/issues/66#issuecomment-468370664n[4] https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se8/html/jls-12.html#jls-12.4n[5] https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se8/html/jls-12.html#jls-12.5n

Workaround coveralls upload failure on Travis CIOur Travis CI builds are configured to run the Gradle `coveralls` tasknto upload test coverage information to coveralls.io.nnHowever, when our Travis CI builds are also configured to use JDK 11,nthe following error occurs when running the `coveralls` task:nn> Task :coveralls FAILEDnservice name: travis-cinservice job id: 520624518nrepo token: nullnnFAILURE: Build failed with an exception.nn* What went wrong:nExecution failed for task ':coveralls'.n> javax.net.ssl.SSLProtocolException: Connection reset by peer (Write failed)nnThis is because JDK 11 implements support for TLS v1.3 [1], and willnattempt to use it if the server also supports it (coveralls.io does).nHowever, a bug [2] in its TLS v1.3 implementation causes it to sendninvalid data to coveralls.io. When coveralls.io receives this invalidndata, it terminates the connection, hence the error occurs.nnLet's workaround this problem by disabling TLS v1.3 support in the JDK.nThis workaround should be fine for now, since not many servers supportnTLS v1.3 yet as the TLS v1.3 spec was only published on Aug 2018 [3].nFurthermore, JDK developers have already acknowledged the bug [2] andntargeted its fix for JDK 13 (i.e. in the near future).nn[1] http://openjdk.java.net/jeps/332n[2] https://bugs.openjdk.java.net/browse/JDK-8221253n[3] https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transport_Layer_Security#TLS_1.3nnCo-authored-by: Paul Tan <pyokagan@gmail.com>n

Upgrade to JDK 11We currently advertise that we support JDK 8. However, the publicnupdates of Java SE 8 for personal users will end soon [1].nnJDK 11 is the next Long-Term-Support (LTS) release after JDK 8 [1].nIt is better for us to keep updated with the latest release of JDK.nnLet's update our target JDK to version 11, with the following steps:nn  * We use openjfx-monocle version jdk-11+26 since that is the latestnversion of openjfx-monocle that supports JDK 11 [2].nn  * We bump the target and source compatibility of Gradle to JDK11.nn  * We update Travis and AppVeyor configs to use JDK11 as runtimenenvironment.nn  * We remove the add-on in Travis config because it is redundant fornJDK 11 [3].nn  * We make it clear in the User Guide / Developer Guide that we onlynsupport JDK 11 and above (not JDK 8, 9, 10).nn[1] https://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/java-se-support-roadmap.htmln[2] https://github.com/TestFX/Monoclen[3] https://docs.travis-ci.com/user/languages/java/#using-java-10-and-latern
